# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: dielectric-materials
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p01] A **capacitor** is a device that stores electrical energy by accumulating electric charges on two closely spaced surfaces that are insulated from each other.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p01] It is a passive electronic component with two terminals.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p01] A capacitor was originally known as a **condenser**, a term still encountered in a few compound names, such as the *condenser microphone*.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p01] Colloquially, a capacitor may be called a ***cap***.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p01] The utility of a capacitor depends on its capacitance.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p01] While some capacitance exists between any two electrical conductors in proximity in a circuit, a capacitor is a component designed specifically to add capacitance to some part of the circuit.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p01] The physical form and construction of practical capacitors vary widely and many types of capacitor are in common use.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p01] Most capacitors contain at least two electrical conductors, often in the form of metallic plates or surfaces separated by a dielectric medium.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p01] A conductor may be a foil, thin film, sintered bead of metal, or an electrolyte.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p01] The nonconducting dielectric acts to increase the capacitor's charge capacity.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p01] Materials commonly used as dielectrics include glass, ceramic, plastic film, paper, mica, air, and oxide layers.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p01] No current actually flows through a perfect dielectric.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p01] However, there is a flow of charge through the source circuit.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p01] If the condition is maintained sufficiently long, the current through the source circuit ceases.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p01] If a time-varying voltage is applied across the leads of the capacitor, the source experiences an ongoing current due to the charging and discharging cycles of the capacitor.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p01] Capacitors are widely used as parts of electrical circuits in many common electrical devices.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p01] Unlike a resistor, an ideal capacitor does not dissipate energy, although real-life capacitors do dissipate a small amount .
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p01] The earliest forms of capacitors were created in the 1740s, when European experimenters discovered that electric charge could be stored in water-filled glass jars that came to be known as Leyden jars.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p01] Today, capacitors are widely used in electronic circuits for blocking direct current while allowing alternating current to pass.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p01] In analog filter networks, they smooth the output of power supplies.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p01] In resonant circuits they tune radios to particular frequencies.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p01] In electric power transmission systems, they stabilize voltage and power flow.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p01] The property of energy storage in capacitors was exploited as dynamic memory in early digital computers, and still is in modern DRAM.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p01] The most common example of natural capacitance are the static charges accumulated between clouds in the sky and the surface of the Earth, where the air between them serves as the dielectric.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p01] This results in bolts of lightning when the breakdown voltage of the air is exceeded.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p01] In October 1745, Ewald Georg von Kleist of Pomerania, Germany, found that charge could be stored by connecting a high-voltage electrostatic generator by a wire to a volume of water in a hand-held glass jar.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p01] Von Kleist's hand and the water acted as conductors and the jar as a dielectric (although details of the mechanism were incorrectly identified at the time).
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p01] Von Kleist found that touching the wire resulted in a powerful spark, much more painful than that obtained from an electrostatic machine.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p01] The following year, the Dutch physicist Pieter van Musschenbroek invented a similar capacitor, which was named the Leyden jar, after the University of Leiden where he worked.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p01] Daniel Gralath was the first to combine several jars in parallel to increase the charge storage capacity.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p01] Benjamin Franklin investigated the Leyden jar and came to the conclusion that the charge was stored on the glass, not in the water as others had assumed.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p01] He also adopted the term "battery", (denoting the increase of power with a row of similar units as in a battery of cannon), subsequently applied to clusters of electrochemical cells.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p01] In 1747, Leyden jars were made by coating the inside and outside of jars with metal foil, leaving a space at the mouth to prevent arcing between the foils.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p01] The earliest unit of capacitance was the jar, equivalent to about 1.11 nanofarads.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p01] More compact construction methods began to be used, such as a flexible dielectric sheet (like oiled paper) sandwiched between sheets of metal foil, rolled or folded into a small package.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p01] Early capacitors were known as *condensers*, a term that is still occasionally used today, particularly in high power applications, such as automotive systems.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p01] The term became deprecated because of the ambiguous meaning of steam condenser, with *capacitor* being recommended by the British Engineering Standards Association in 1926, although it took several decades for the term to predominate.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p01] Since the beginning of the study of electricity, non-conductive materials like glass, porcelain, paper and mica have been used as insulators.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p01] Decades later, these materials were also well-suited for use as the dielectric for the first capacitors.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p01] Paper capacitors, made by sandwiching a strip of impregnated paper between strips of metal and rolling the result into a cylinder, were commonly used in the late 19th century; their manufacture started in 1876, and they were used from the early 20th century as decoupling capacitors in telephony.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p01] Porcelain was used in the first ceramic capacitors.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p01] In the early years of Marconi's wireless transmitting apparatus, porcelain capacitors were used for high voltage and high frequency application in the transmitters.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p01] On the receiver side, smaller mica capacitors were used for resonant circuits.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p01] Mica capacitors were invented in 1909 by William Dubilier.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p01] Prior to World War II, mica was the most common dielectric for capacitors in the United States.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p01] Charles Pollak (born Karol Pollak), the inventor of the first electrolytic capacitors, found out that the oxide layer on an aluminum anode remained stable in a neutral or alkaline electrolyte, even when the power was switched off.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p01] 672,913 for an "Electric liquid capacitor with aluminum electrodes".
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p01] Solid electrolyte tantalum capacitors were invented by Bell Laboratories in the early 1950s as a miniaturized and more reliable low-voltage support capacitor to complement their newly invented transistor.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p01] With the development of plastic materials by organic chemists during the Second World War, the capacitor industry began to replace paper with thinner polymer films.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p01] One very early development in film capacitors was described in British Patent 587,953 in 1944.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p01] Electric double-layer capacitors (now supercapacitors) were invented in 1957 when H.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p01] Becker developed a "Low voltage electrolytic capacitor with porous carbon electrodes".
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p01] He believed that the energy was stored as a charge in the carbon pores used in his capacitor as in the pores of the etched foils of electrolytic capacitors.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p01] The MOS capacitor was later widely adopted as a storage capacitor in memory chips, and as the basic building block of the charge-coupled device (CCD) in image sensor technology.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p01] Robert Dennard invented modern DRAM architecture, combining a single MOS transistor per capacitor.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p01] A capacitor consists of two conductors separated by a non-conductive region.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p01] The non-conductive region can either be a vacuum or an electrical insulator material known as a dielectric.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p01] Examples of dielectric media are glass, air, paper, plastic, ceramic, and even a semiconductor depletion region chemically identical to the conductors.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p01] From Coulomb's law, a charge on one conductor will exert a force on the charge carriers within the other conductor, attracting opposite polarity charge and repelling like polarity charges, thus an opposite polarity charge will be induced on the surface of the other conductor.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p01] The conductors thus hold equal and opposite charges on their facing surfaces, and the dielectric develops an electric field.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p01] A capacitance of one farad (1 F) means that one coulomb of charge on each conductor causes a voltage of one volt across the device.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p01] Because the conductors (or plates) are close together, the opposite charges on the conductors attract one another due to their electric fields, allowing the capacitor to store more charge for a given voltage than when the conductors are separated, yielding a larger capacitance.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p01] In practical devices, charge build-up sometimes affects the capacitor mechanically, causing its capacitance to vary.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p01] In the hydraulic analogy, voltage is analogous to water pressure and electrical current through a wire is analogous to water flow through a pipe.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p01] A capacitor is like an elastic diaphragm within the pipe.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p01] Although water cannot pass through the diaphragm, it moves as the diaphragm stretches or un-stretches.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p01] In a circuit, a capacitor can behave differently at different time instants.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p01] The simplest model of a capacitor consists of two thin parallel conductive plates each with an area of A separated by a uniform gap of thickness d filled with a dielectric of permittivity ⁠ $\varepsilon$ ⁠.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p01] It is assumed the gap d is much smaller than the dimensions of the plates.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p01] This model applies well to many practical capacitors which are constructed of metal sheets separated by a thin layer of insulating dielectric, since manufacturers try to keep the dielectric very uniform in thickness to avoid thin spots which can cause failure of the capacitor.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p01] This "fringing field" area is approximately the same width as the plate separation, ⁠ d ⁠, and assuming d is small compared to the plate dimensions, it is small enough to be ignored.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p01] From Gauss's law the magnitude of the electric field between the plates is ⁠ $\textstyle E={\sigma \over \varepsilon }$ ⁠.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p01] Therefore, in a capacitor the highest capacitance is achieved with a high permittivity dielectric material, large plate area, and small separation between the plates.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p01] Since the area A of the plates increases with the square of the linear dimensions and the separation d increases linearly, the capacitance scales with the linear dimension of a capacitor (⁠ $C\varpropto L$ ⁠), or as the cube root of the volume.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p01] A parallel plate capacitor can only store a finite amount of energy before dielectric breakdown occurs.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p01] The capacitor's dielectric material has a dielectric strength *U*d which sets the capacitor's breakdown voltage at *V* = *V*bd = *U*d*d*.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p01] The maximum energy is a function of dielectric volume, permittivity, and dielectric strength.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p01] Changing the plate area and the separation between the plates while maintaining the same volume causes no change of the maximum amount of energy that the capacitor can store, so long as the distance between plates remains much smaller than both the length and width of the plates.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p01] In addition, these equations assume that the electric field is entirely concentrated in the dielectric between the plates.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p01] In reality there are fringing fields outside the dielectric, for example between the sides of the capacitor plates, which increase the effective capacitance of the capacitor.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p01] This is sometimes called parasitic capacitance.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p01] For some simple capacitor geometries this additional capacitance term can be calculated analytically.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p01] It becomes negligibly small when the ratios of plate width to separation and length to separation are large.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p01] For n number of plates in a capacitor, the total capacitance would be $C=\varepsilon _{o}{\frac {A}{d}}(n-1)$ where ${\textstyle C={\frac {\varepsilon _{o}A}{d}}}$ is the capacitance for a single plate and n is the number of interleaved plates.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p01] As shown to the figure on the right, the interleaved plates can be seen as parallel plates connected to each other.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p01] Every pair of adjacent plates acts as a separate capacitor; the number of pairs is always one less than the number of plates, hence the $(n-1)$ multiplier.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p01] To increase the charge and voltage on a capacitor, work must be done by an external power source to move charge from the negative to the positive plate against the opposing force of the electric field.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p01] If the voltage on the capacitor is ⁠ V ⁠, the work $\mathrm {d} W$ required to move a small increment of charge $\mathrm {d} q$ from the negative to the positive plate is ⁠ $\mathrm {d} W=V\mathop {} \!\mathrm {d} q$ ⁠.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p01] The energy is stored in the increased electric field between the plates.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p01] This potential energy will remain in the capacitor until the charge is removed.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p01] If charge is allowed to move back from the positive to the negative plate, for example by connecting a circuit with resistance between the plates, the charge moving under the influence of the electric field will do work on the external circuit.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p01] If the gap between the capacitor plates d is constant, as in the parallel plate model above, the electric field between the plates will be uniform (neglecting fringing fields) and will have a constant value ⁠ $E=V/d$ ⁠.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p01] The current $I(t)$ through any component in an electric circuit is defined as the rate of flow of a charge $Q(t)$ passing through it.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p01] Actual charges – electrons – cannot pass through the dielectric of an *ideal* capacitor.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p01] Rather, one electron accumulates on the negative plate for each one that leaves the positive plate, resulting in an electron depletion and consequent positive charge on one electrode that is equal and opposite to the accumulated negative charge on the other.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p01] Thus the charge on the electrodes is equal to the integral of the current as well as proportional to the voltage, as discussed above.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p01] As with any antiderivative, a constant of integration is added to represent the initial voltage ⁠ $V(t_{0})$ ⁠).
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p01] for C independent of time, voltage and electric charge.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p01] The dual of the capacitor is the inductor, which stores energy in a magnetic field rather than an electric field.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p01] Its current-voltage relation is obtained by exchanging current and voltage in the capacitor equations and replacing C with the inductance L.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p01] A series circuit containing only a resistor, a capacitor, a switch and a constant DC source of voltage *V*0 is known as a *charging circuit*.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p01] At *t* = 0, the voltage across the capacitor is zero and the voltage across the resistor is *V*0.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p01] The initial current is then ⁠ $\textstyle I(0)={V_{0} \over R}$ ⁠.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p01] As the capacitor reaches equilibrium with the source voltage, the voltages across the resistor and the current through the entire circuit decay exponentially.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p01] In the case of a *discharging* capacitor, the capacitor's initial voltage (*V*Ci) replaces *V*0.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p01] Impedance, the vector sum of reactance and resistance, describes the phase difference and the ratio of amplitudes between sinusoidally varying voltage and sinusoidally varying current at a given frequency.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p01] Fourier analysis allows any signal to be constructed from a spectrum of frequencies, whence the circuit's reaction to the various frequencies may be found.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p01] The ⁠ $-j$ ⁠ phase indicates that the AC voltage ⁠ $V=ZI$ ⁠ lags the AC current by 90°: the positive current phase corresponds to increasing voltage as the capacitor charges; zero current corresponds to instantaneous constant voltage.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p01] Impedance decreases with increasing capacitance and increasing frequency.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p01] This implies that a higher-frequency signal or a larger capacitor results in a lower voltage amplitude per current amplitude – an AC "short circuit" or AC coupling.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p01] Conversely, for very low frequencies, the reactance is high, so that a capacitor is nearly an open circuit in AC analysis – those frequencies have been "filtered out".
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p01] Capacitors are different from resistors and inductors in that the impedance is *inversely* proportional to the defining characteristic; i.e., capacitance.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p01] A capacitor connected to an alternating voltage source has a displacement current to flowing through it.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p01] At ⁠ $\sin(\omega t)=-1$ ⁠, the capacitor has a maximum (or peak) current whereby ⁠ $I_{0}=\omega CV_{0}$ ⁠.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p01] In this situation, the current is out of phase with the voltage by ⁠ $\textstyle +{\pi \over 2}$ ⁠ radians or +90 degrees, i.e. the current leads the voltage by 90°.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p01] Capacitors in a parallel configuration each have the same applied voltage.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p01] Charge is apportioned among them by capacitance value.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p01] Connected in series, the schematic diagram reveals that the separation distance, not the plate area, adds up.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p01] The capacitors each store instantaneous charge build-up equal to that of every other capacitor in the series.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p01] The total voltage difference from end to end is apportioned to each capacitor according to the inverse of its capacitance.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p01] Capacitors are combined in series to achieve a higher working voltage, for example for smoothing a high voltage power supply.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p01] The voltage ratings, which are based on plate separation, add up, if capacitance and leakage currents for each capacitor are identical.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p01] In such an application, on occasion, series strings are connected in parallel, forming a matrix.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p01] The goal is to maximize the energy storage of the network without overloading any capacitor.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p01] For high-energy storage with capacitors in series, some safety considerations must be applied to ensure one capacitor failing and leaking current does not apply too much voltage to the other series capacitors.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p01] Series connection is also sometimes used to adapt polarized electrolytic capacitors for bipolar AC use.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p01] (Note that this is only correct if all capacitance values are equal).
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p01] In practice, capacitors deviate from the ideal capacitor equation in several aspects.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p01] Some of these, such as leakage current and parasitic effects are linear, or can be analyzed as nearly linear, and can be accounted for by adding virtual components to form an equivalent circuit.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p01] The usual methods of network analysis can then be applied.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p01] In other cases, such as with breakdown voltage, the effect is non-linear and ordinary (normal, e.g., linear) network analysis cannot be used, the effect must be considered separately.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p01] Yet another group of artifacts may exist, including temperature dependence, that may be linear but invalidates the assumption in the analysis that capacitance is a constant.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p01] Finally, combined parasitic effects such as inherent inductance, resistance, or dielectric losses can exhibit non-uniform behavior at varying frequencies of operation.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p01] Above a particular electric field strength, known as the dielectric strength ⁠ $E_{\mathrm {ds} }$ ⁠, the dielectric in a capacitor becomes conductive.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p01] The maximum energy that can be stored safely in a capacitor is limited by the breakdown voltage.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p01] Exceeding this voltage can result in a short circuit between the plates, which can often cause permanent damage to the dielectric, plates, or both.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p01] Due to the scaling of capacitance and breakdown voltage with dielectric thickness, all capacitors made with a particular dielectric have approximately equal maximum energy density, to the extent that the dielectric dominates their volume.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p01] For air dielectric capacitors the breakdown field strength is of the order 2–5 MV/m (or equivalently in kilovolts per millimeter); for mica the breakdown is 100–300 MV/m; for oil, 15–25 MV/m; it can be much less when other materials are used for the dielectric.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p01] The dielectric is used in very thin layers and so absolute breakdown voltage of capacitors is limited.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p01] Typical ratings for capacitors used for general electronics applications range from a few volts to 1 kilovolt.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p01] As the voltage increases, the dielectric must be thicker, making high-voltage capacitors larger per capacitance than those rated for lower voltages.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p01] The breakdown voltage is critically affected by factors such as the geometry of the capacitor conductive parts; sharp edges or points increase the electric field strength at that point and can lead to a local breakdown.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p01] Once this starts to happen, the breakdown quickly tracks through the dielectric until it reaches the opposite plate, leaving carbon behind and causing a short (or relatively low resistance) circuit.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p01] The results can be explosive, as the short in the capacitor draws current from the surrounding circuitry and dissipates the energy.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p01] However, in capacitors with particular dielectrics and thin metal electrodes, shorts are not formed after breakdown.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p01] It happens because a metal melts or evaporates in a breakdown vicinity, isolating it from the rest of the capacitor.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p01] The usual breakdown route is that the field strength becomes large enough to pull electrons in the dielectric from their atoms thus causing conduction.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p01] Other scenarios are possible, such as impurities in the dielectric, and, if the dielectric is of a crystalline nature, imperfections in the crystal structure can result in an avalanche breakdown as seen in semi-conductor devices.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p01] Breakdown voltage is also affected by pressure, humidity and temperature.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p01] An ideal capacitor only stores and releases electrical energy, without dissipation.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p01] As frequency increases, the capacitive impedance (a negative reactance) reduces, so the dielectric's conductance becomes less important and the series components become more significant.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p01] Thus, a simplified RLC series model valid for a large frequency range simply treats the capacitor as being in series with an equivalent series inductance ${\text{ESL}}$ and a frequency-dependent *equivalent series resistance* ${\text{ESR}}$ , which varies little with frequency.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p01] Unlike the previous model, this model is not valid at DC and very low frequencies where $G_{\text{dielectric}}$ is relevant.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p01] Inductive reactance increases with frequency.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p01] Because its sign is positive, it counteracts the capacitance.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p01] At the RLC circuit's natural frequency $\omega _{0}{=}{\tfrac {1}{\sqrt {{\text{ESL}}\cdot {\text{C}}}}}$ , the inductance perfectly cancels the capacitance, so total reactance is zero.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p01] Since the total impedance at $\omega _{0}$ is just the real-value of ${\text{ESR}}$ , average power dissipation reaches its maximum of ⁠VRMS2/ESR⁠, where VRMS is the root mean square (RMS) voltage across the capacitor.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p01] At even higher frequencies, the inductive impedance dominates, so the capacitor undesirably behaves instead like an inductor.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p01] High-frequency engineering involves accounting for the inductance of all connections and components.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p01] The ⁠ Q ⁠ factor is a measure of its efficiency: the higher the ⁠ Q ⁠ factor of the capacitor, the closer it approaches the behavior of an ideal capacitor.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p01] Ripple current is the AC component of an applied source (often a switched-mode power supply) whose frequency may be constant or varying.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p01] Ripple current causes heat to be generated within the capacitor due to the dielectric losses caused by the changing field strength together with the current flow across the slightly resistive supply lines or the electrolyte in the capacitor.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p01] The equivalent series resistance (ESR) is the amount of internal series resistance one would add to a perfect capacitor to model this.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p01] Some types of capacitors, primarily tantalum and aluminum electrolytic capacitors, as well as some film capacitors have a specified rating value for maximum ripple current.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p01] The capacitance of certain capacitors decreases as the component ages.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p01] In ceramic capacitors, this is caused by degradation of the dielectric.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p01] The type of dielectric, ambient operating and storage temperatures are the most significant aging factors, while the operating voltage usually has a smaller effect, i.e., usual capacitor design is to minimize voltage coefficient.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p01] The aging process may be reversed by heating the component above the Curie point.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p01] Aging is fastest near the beginning of life of the component, and the device stabilizes over time.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p01] Electrolytic capacitors age as the electrolyte evaporates.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p01] In contrast with ceramic capacitors, this occurs towards the end of life of the component.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p01] Temperature dependence of capacitance is usually expressed in parts per million (ppm) per °C.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p01] It can usually be taken as a broadly linear function but can be noticeably non-linear at the temperature extremes.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p01] The temperature coefficient may be positive or negative, depending mostly on the dielectric material.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p01] Some, designated C0G/NP0, but called **NPO**, have a somewhat negative coefficient at one temperature, positive at another, and zero in between.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p01] Such components may be specified for temperature-critical circuits.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p01] Capacitors, especially ceramic capacitors, and older designs such as paper capacitors, can absorb sound waves resulting in a microphonic effect.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p01] Vibration moves the plates, causing the capacitance to vary, in turn inducing AC current.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p01] Some dielectrics also generate piezoelectricity.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p01] The resulting interference is especially problematic in audio applications, potentially causing feedback or unintended recording.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p01] In the reverse microphonic effect, the varying electric field between the capacitor plates exerts a physical force, moving them as a speaker.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p01] This can generate audible sound, but drains energy and stresses the dielectric and the electrolyte, if any.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p01] Current reversal occurs when the current changes direction.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p01] Voltage reversal is the change of polarity in a circuit.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p01] Reversal is generally described as the percentage of the maximum rated voltage that reverses polarity.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p01] In DC circuits, this is usually less than 100%, often in the range of 0 to 90%, whereas AC circuits experience 100% reversal.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p01] In DC circuits and pulsed circuits, current and voltage reversal are affected by the damping of the system.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p01] Voltage reversal is encountered in RLC circuits that are underdamped.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p01] The current and voltage reverse direction, forming a harmonic oscillator between the inductance and capacitance.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p01] The current and voltage tends to oscillate and may reverse direction several times, with each peak being lower than the previous, until the system reaches an equilibrium.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p01] In comparison, critically damped or overdamped systems usually do not experience a voltage reversal.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p01] Reversal is also encountered in AC circuits, where the peak current is equal in each direction.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p01] For maximum life, capacitors usually need to be able to handle the maximum amount of reversal that a system may experience.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p01] An AC circuit experiences 100% voltage reversal, while underdamped DC circuits experience less than 100%.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p01] Reversal creates excess electric fields in the dielectric, causes excess heating of both the dielectric and the conductors, and can dramatically shorten the life expectancy of the capacitor.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p01] Reversal ratings often affect the design considerations for the capacitor, from the choice of dielectric materials and voltage ratings to the types of internal connections used.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p01] Capacitors made with any type of dielectric material show some level of "dielectric absorption" or "soakage".
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p01] On discharging a capacitor and disconnecting it, after a short time it may develop a voltage due to hysteresis in the dielectric.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p01] This effect is objectionable in applications such as precision sample and hold circuits or timing circuits.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p01] The level of absorption depends on many factors, from design considerations to charging time, since the absorption is a time-dependent process.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p01] However, the primary factor is the type of dielectric material.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p01] Capacitors such as tantalum electrolytic or polysulfone film exhibit relatively high absorption, while polystyrene or Teflon allow very small levels of absorption.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p01] In some capacitors where dangerous voltages and energies exist, such as in flashtubes, television sets, microwave ovens and defibrillators, the dielectric absorption can recharge the capacitor to hazardous voltages after it has been shorted or discharged.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p01] Any capacitor containing over 10 joules of energy is generally considered hazardous, while 50 joules or higher is potentially lethal.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p01] A capacitor may regain anywhere from 0.01 to 20% of its original charge over a period of several minutes, allowing a seemingly safe capacitor to become surprisingly dangerous.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p01] No material is a perfect insulator, thus all dielectrics allow some small level of current to leak through, which can be measured with a megohmmeter.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p01] Leakage is equivalent to a resistor in parallel with the capacitor.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p01] Constant exposure to factors such as heat, mechanical stress, or humidity can cause the dielectric to deteriorate resulting in excessive leakage, a problem often seen in older vacuum tube circuits, particularly where oiled paper and foil capacitors were used.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p01] In many vacuum tube circuits, interstage coupling capacitors are used to conduct a varying signal from the plate of one tube to the grid circuit of the next stage.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p01] A leaky capacitor can cause the grid circuit voltage to be raised from its normal bias setting, causing excessive current or signal distortion in the downstream tube.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p01] In power amplifiers this can cause the plates to glow red, or current limiting resistors to overheat, even fail.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p01] Similar considerations apply to component fabricated solid-state (transistor) amplifiers, but, owing to lower heat production and the use of modern polyester dielectric-barriers, this once-common problem has become relatively rare.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p01] Aluminum electrolytic capacitors are *conditioned* when manufactured by applying a voltage sufficient to initiate the proper internal chemical state.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p01] This state is maintained by regular use of the equipment.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p01] If a system using electrolytic capacitors is unused for a long period of time it can lose its conditioning.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p01] Sometimes they fail with a short circuit when next operated.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p01] All capacitors have varying lifespans, depending upon their construction, operational conditions, and environmental conditions.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p01] Solid-state ceramic capacitors generally have very long lives under normal use, which has little dependency on factors such as vibration or ambient temperature, but factors like humidity, mechanical stress, and fatigue play a primary role in their failure.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p01] Some capacitors may experience a gradual loss of capacitance, increased leakage or an increase in equivalent series resistance (ESR), while others may fail suddenly or even catastrophically.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p01] For example, metal-film capacitors are more prone to damage from stress and humidity, but will self-heal when a breakdown in the dielectric occurs.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p01] The formation of a glow discharge at the point of failure prevents arcing by vaporizing the metallic film in that spot, neutralizing any short circuit with minimal loss in capacitance.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p01] When enough pinholes accumulate in the film, a total failure occurs in a metal-film capacitor, generally happening suddenly without warning.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p01] Electrolytic capacitors generally have the shortest lifespans.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p01] Electrolytic capacitors are affected very little by vibration or humidity, but factors such as ambient and operational temperatures play a large role in their failure, which gradually occur as an increase in ESR (up to 300%) and as much as a 20% decrease in capacitance.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p01] The capacitors contain electrolytes which will eventually diffuse through the seals and evaporate.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p01] An increase in temperature also increases internal pressure, and increases the reaction rate of the chemicals.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p01] Manufacturers often use this equation to supply an expected lifespan, in hours, for electrolytic capacitors when used at their designed operating temperature, which is affected by both ambient temperature, ESR, and ripple current.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p01] However, these ideal conditions may not exist in every use.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p02] Practical capacitors are available commercially in many different forms.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p02] The type of internal dielectric, the structure of the plates and the device packaging all strongly affect the characteristics of the capacitor, and its applications.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p02] Values available range from very low (picofarad range; while arbitrarily low values are in principle possible, stray (parasitic) capacitance in any circuit is the limiting factor) to about 5 kF supercapacitors.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p02] Above approximately 1 microfarad electrolytic capacitors are usually used because of their small size and low cost compared with other types, unless their relatively poor stability, life and polarised nature make them unsuitable.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p02] Very high capacity supercapacitors use a porous carbon-based electrode material.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p02] Most capacitors have a dielectric spacer, which increases their capacitance compared to air or a vacuum.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p02] In order to maximise the charge that a capacitor can hold, the dielectric material needs to have as high a permittivity as possible, while also having as high a breakdown voltage as possible.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p02] The dielectric also needs to have as low a loss with frequency as possible.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p02] However, low value capacitors are available with a high vacuum between their plates to allow extremely high voltage operation and low losses.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p02] Variable capacitors with their plates open to the atmosphere were commonly used in radio tuning circuits.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p02] Later designs use polymer foil dielectric between the moving and stationary plates, with no significant air space between the plates.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p02] Several solid dielectrics are available, including paper, plastic, glass, mica and ceramic.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p02] Paper was used extensively in older capacitors and offers relatively high voltage performance.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p02] However, paper absorbs moisture, and has been largely replaced by plastic film capacitors.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p02] Large plastic film capacitors are used extensively in suppression circuits, motor start circuits, and power-factor correction circuits.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p02] Ceramic capacitors are generally small, cheap and useful for high frequency applications, although their capacitance varies strongly with voltage and temperature and they age poorly.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p02] They can also suffer from the piezoelectric effect.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p02] Ceramic capacitors are broadly categorized as class 1 dielectrics, which have predictable variation of capacitance with temperature or class 2 dielectrics, which can operate at higher voltage.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p02] Modern multilayer ceramics are usually quite small, but some types have inherently wide value tolerances, microphonic issues, and are usually physically brittle.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p02] Glass and mica capacitors are extremely reliable, stable and tolerant to high temperatures and voltages, but are too expensive for most mainstream applications.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p02] Electrolytic capacitors use an aluminum or tantalum plate with an oxide dielectric layer.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p02] The second electrode is a liquid electrolyte, connected to the circuit by another foil plate.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p02] Electrolytic capacitors offer very high capacitance but suffer from poor tolerances, high instability, gradual loss of capacitance especially when subjected to heat, and high leakage current.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p02] Poor quality capacitors may leak electrolyte, which is harmful to printed circuit boards.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p02] The conductivity of the electrolyte drops at low temperatures, which increases equivalent series resistance.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p02] While widely used for power-supply conditioning, poor high-frequency characteristics make them unsuitable for many applications.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p02] Electrolytic capacitors suffer from self-degradation if unused for a period (around a year), and when full power is applied may short circuit, permanently damaging the capacitor and usually blowing a fuse or causing failure of rectifier diodes.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p02] For example, in older equipment, this may cause arcing in rectifier tubes.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p02] They can be restored before use by gradually applying the operating voltage, often performed on antique vacuum tube equipment over a period of thirty minutes by using a variable transformer to supply AC power.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p02] The use of this technique may be less satisfactory for some solid state equipment, which may be damaged by operation below its normal power range, requiring that the power supply first be isolated from the consuming circuits.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p02] Such remedies may not be applicable to modern high-frequency power supplies as these produce full output voltage even with reduced input.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p02] Tantalum capacitors offer better frequency and temperature characteristics than aluminum, but higher dielectric absorption and leakage.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p02] Polymer capacitors (OS-CON, OC-CON, KO, AO) use solid conductive polymer (or polymerized organic semiconductor) as electrolyte and offer longer life and lower ESR at higher cost than standard electrolytic capacitors.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p02] A feedthrough capacitor is a component that, while not serving as its main use, has capacitance and is used to conduct signals through a conductive sheet.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p02] Several other types of capacitor are available for specialist applications.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p02] Supercapacitors store large amounts of energy.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p02] Supercapacitors made from carbon aerogel, carbon nanotubes, or highly porous electrode materials, offer extremely high capacitance (up to 5 kF as of 2010) and can be used in some applications instead of rechargeable batteries.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p02] Alternating current capacitors are specifically designed to work on line (mains) voltage AC power circuits.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p02] They are commonly used in electric motor circuits and are often designed to handle large currents, so they tend to be physically large.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p02] They are usually ruggedly packaged, often in metal cases that can be easily grounded/earthed.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p02] They also are designed with direct current breakdown voltages of at least five times the maximum AC voltage.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p02] The dielectric constant for a number of very useful dielectrics changes as a function of the applied electrical field, for example ferroelectric materials, so the capacitance for these devices is more complex.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p02] This field polarizes the dielectric, which polarization, in the case of a ferroelectric, is a nonlinear *S*-shaped function of the electric field, which, in the case of a large area parallel plate device, translates into a capacitance that is a nonlinear function of the voltage.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p02] Corresponding to the voltage-dependent capacitance, to charge the capacitor to voltage V an integral relation is found: $Q=\int _{0}^{V}C(V)\mathop {} \!\mathrm {d} V$ which agrees with *Q* = *CV* only when C does not depend on voltage V.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p02] The nonlinear capacitance of a microscope probe scanned along a ferroelectric surface is used to study the domain structure of ferroelectric materials.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p02] Another example of voltage dependent capacitance occurs in semiconductor devices such as semiconductor diodes, where the voltage dependence stems not from a change in dielectric constant but in a voltage dependence of the spacing between the charges on the two sides of the capacitor.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p02] This effect is intentionally exploited in diode-like devices known as varicaps.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p02] If a capacitor is driven with a time-varying voltage that changes rapidly enough, at some frequency the polarization of the dielectric cannot follow the voltage.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p02] As an example of the origin of this mechanism, the internal microscopic dipoles contributing to the dielectric constant cannot move instantly, and so as frequency of an applied alternating voltage increases, the dipole response is limited and the dielectric constant diminishes.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p02] A changing dielectric constant with frequency is referred to as dielectric dispersion, and is governed by dielectric relaxation processes, such as Debye relaxation.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p02] indicating the lag in response by the time dependence of *εr*, calculated in principle from an underlying microscopic analysis, for example, of the dipole behavior in the dielectric.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p02] See, for example, linear response function.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p02] The integral extends over the entire past history up to the present time.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p02] where *ε*r(*ω*) is now a complex function, with an imaginary part related to absorption of energy from the field by the medium.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p02] The capacitance, being proportional to the dielectric constant, also exhibits this frequency behavior.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p02] (Measurement "without the dielectric" in principle means measurement in free space, an unattainable goal inasmuch as even the quantum vacuum is predicted to exhibit nonideal behavior, such as dichroism.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p02] Using this measurement method, the dielectric constant may exhibit a resonance at certain frequencies corresponding to characteristic response frequencies (excitation energies) of contributors to the dielectric constant.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p02] These resonances are the basis for a number of experimental techniques for detecting defects.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p02] The *conductance method* measures absorption as a function of frequency.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p02] Alternatively, the time response of the capacitance can be used directly, as in *deep-level transient spectroscopy*.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p02] Another example of frequency dependent capacitance occurs with MOS capacitors, where the slow generation of minority carriers means that at high frequencies the capacitance measures only the majority carrier response, while at low frequencies both types of carrier respond.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p02] At optical frequencies, in semiconductors the dielectric constant exhibits structure related to the band structure of the solid.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p02] Sophisticated modulation spectroscopy measurement methods based upon modulating the crystal structure by pressure or by other stresses and observing the related changes in absorption or reflection of light have advanced our knowledge of these materials.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p02] The arrangement of plates and dielectric has many variations in different styles depending on the desired ratings of the capacitor.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p02] For small values of capacitance (microfarads and less), ceramic disks use metallic coatings, with wire leads bonded to the coating.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p02] Larger values can be made by multiple stacks of plates and disks.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p02] Larger value capacitors usually use a metal foil or metal film layer deposited on the surface of a dielectric film to make the plates, and a dielectric film of impregnated paper or plastic – these are rolled up to save space.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p02] To reduce the series resistance and inductance for long plates, the plates and dielectric are staggered so that connection is made at the common edge of the rolled-up plates, not at the ends of the foil or metalized film strips that comprise the plates.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p02] The assembly is encased to prevent moisture entering the dielectric – early radio equipment used a cardboard tube sealed with wax.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p02] Modern paper or film dielectric capacitors are dipped in a hard thermoplastic.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p02] Large capacitors for high-voltage use may have the roll form compressed to fit into a rectangular metal case, with bolted terminals and bushings for connections.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p02] The dielectric in larger capacitors is often impregnated with a liquid to improve its properties.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p02] Capacitors may have their connecting leads arranged in many configurations, for example axially or radially.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p02] "Axial" means that the leads are on a common axis, typically the axis of the capacitor's cylindrical body – the leads extend from opposite ends.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p02] Radial leads are rarely aligned along radii of the body's circle, so the term is conventional.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p02] The leads (until bent) are usually in planes parallel to that of the flat body of the capacitor, and extend in the same direction; they are often parallel as manufactured.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p02] Small, cheap discoidal ceramic capacitors have existed from the 1930s onward, and remain in widespread use.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p02] After the 1980s, surface mount packages for capacitors have been widely used.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p02] These packages are extremely small and lack connecting leads, allowing them to be soldered directly onto the surface of printed circuit boards.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p02] Surface mount components avoid undesirable high-frequency effects due to the leads and simplify automated assembly, although manual handling is made difficult due to their small size.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p02] Mechanically controlled variable capacitors allow the plate spacing to be adjusted, for example by rotating or sliding a set of movable plates into alignment with a set of stationary plates.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p02] Low cost variable capacitors squeeze together alternating layers of aluminum and plastic with a screw.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p02] Electrical control of capacitance is achievable with varactors (or varicaps), which are reverse-biased semiconductor diodes whose depletion region width varies with applied voltage.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p02] They are used in phase-locked loops, amongst other applications.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p02] Most capacitors have designations printed on their bodies to indicate their electrical characteristics.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p02] Larger capacitors, such as electrolytic types usually display the capacitance as value with explicit unit, for example, *220 μF*.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p02] For typographical reasons, some manufacturers print *MF* on capacitors to indicate microfarads (μF).
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p02] Smaller capacitors, such as ceramic types, often use a shorthand-notation consisting of three digits and an optional letter, where the digits (*XYZ*) denote the capacitance in picofarad (pF), calculated as *XY* × 10*Z*, and the letter indicating the tolerance.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p02] Common tolerances are ±5%, ±10%, and ±20%, denoted as J, K, and M, respectively.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p02] A capacitor may also be labeled with its working voltage, temperature, and other relevant characteristics.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p02] Example: A capacitor labeled or designated as *473K 330V* has a capacitance of 47×103 pF = 47 nF (±10%) with a maximum working voltage of 330 V.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p02] The working voltage of a capacitor is nominally the highest voltage that may be applied across it without undue risk of breaking down the dielectric layer.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p02] The code consists of an uppercase letter denoting the two significant digits of the value followed by a digit indicating the multiplier.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p02] The EIA standard also defines a number of lowercase letters to specify a number of values not found in E24.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p02] The RKM code following IEC 60062 and BS 1852 is a notation to state a capacitor's value in a circuit diagram.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p02] It avoids using a decimal separator and replaces the decimal separator with the SI prefix symbol for the particular value (and the letter F for weight 1).
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p02] The code is also used for part markings.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p02] In texts prior to the 1960s and on some capacitor packages until more recently, obsolete capacitance units were utilized in electronic books, magazines, and electronics catalogs.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p02] The old units "mfd" and "mf" meant *microfarad* (μF); and the old units "mmfd", "mmf", "uuf", "μμf", "pfd" meant *picofarad* (pF); but they are rarely used any more.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p02] Also, "Micromicrofarad" or "micro-microfarad" are obsolete units that are found in some older texts that is equivalent to *picofarad* (pF).
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p02] A capacitor can store electric energy when disconnected from its charging circuit, so it can be used like a temporary battery, or like other types of rechargeable energy storage system.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p02] Capacitors are commonly used in electronic devices to maintain power supply while batteries are being changed.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p02] A capacitor can facilitate conversion of kinetic energy of charged particles into electric energy and store it.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p02] There are tradeoffs between capacitors and batteries as storage devices.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p02] Without external resistors or inductors, capacitors can generally release their stored energy in a very short time compared to batteries.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p02] Conversely, batteries can hold a far greater charge per their size.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p02] Conventional capacitors provide less than 360 joules per kilogram of specific energy, whereas a conventional alkaline battery has a density of 590 kJ/kg.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p02] There is an intermediate solution: supercapacitors, which can accept and deliver charge much faster than batteries, and tolerate many more charge and discharge cycles than rechargeable batteries.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p02] They are, however, 10 times larger than conventional batteries for a given charge.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p02] On the other hand, it has been shown that the amount of charge stored in the dielectric layer of the thin film capacitor can be equal to, or can even exceed, the amount of charge stored on its plates.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p02] In car audio systems, large capacitors store energy for the amplifier to use on demand.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p02] Also, for a flash tube, a capacitor is used to hold the high voltage.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p02] In the 1930s, John Atanasoff applied the principle of energy storage in capacitors to construct dynamic digital memories for the first binary computers that used electron tubes for logic.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p02] Pulsed power is used in many applications to increase the power intensity (watts) of a volume of energy (joules) by releasing that volume within a very short time.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p02] Pulses in the nanosecond range and powers in the gigawatts are achievable.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p02] Short pulses often require specially constructed, low-inductance, high-voltage capacitors that are often used in large groups (*capacitor banks*) to supply huge pulses of current for many pulsed power applications.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p02] These include electromagnetic forming, Marx generators, pulsed lasers (especially TEA lasers), pulse forming networks, radar, fusion research, and particle accelerators.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p02] Large capacitor banks (reservoir) are used as energy sources for the exploding-bridgewire detonators or slapper detonators in nuclear weapons and other specialty weapons.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p02] Experimental work is under way using banks of capacitors as power sources for electromagnetic armour and electromagnetic railguns and coilguns.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p02] Reservoir capacitors are used in power supplies where they smooth the output of a full or half wave rectifier.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p02] They can also be used in charge pump circuits as the energy storage element in the generation of higher voltages than the input voltage.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p02] Capacitors are connected in parallel with the power circuits of most electronic devices and larger systems (such as factories) to shunt away and conceal current fluctuations from the primary power source to provide a "clean" power supply for signal or control circuits.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p02] Audio equipment, for example, uses several capacitors in this way, to shunt away power line hum before it gets into the signal circuitry.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p02] The capacitors act as a local reserve for the DC power source, and bypass AC currents from the power supply.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p02] This is used in car audio applications, when a stiffening capacitor compensates for the inductance and resistance of the leads to the lead–acid car battery.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p02] In electric power distribution, capacitors are used for power-factor correction.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p02] Such capacitors often come as three capacitors connected as a three phase load.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p02] Usually, the values of these capacitors are not given in farads but rather as a reactive power in volt-amperes reactive (var).
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p02] The purpose is to counteract inductive loading from devices like electric motors and transmission lines to make the load appear to be mostly resistive.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p02] Individual motor or lamp loads may have capacitors for power-factor correction, or larger sets of capacitors (usually with automatic switching devices) may be installed at a load center within a building or in a large utility substation.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p02] Because capacitors pass AC but block DC signals (when charged up to the applied DC voltage), they are often used to separate the AC and DC components of a signal.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p02] This method is known as *AC coupling* or "capacitive coupling".
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p02] Here, a large value of capacitance, whose value need not be accurately controlled, but whose reactance is small at the signal frequency, is employed.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p02] A decoupling capacitor is a capacitor used to protect one part of a circuit from the effect of another, for instance to suppress noise or transients.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p02] Noise caused by other circuit elements is shunted through the capacitor, reducing the effect they have on the rest of the circuit.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p02] It is most commonly used between the power supply and ground.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p02] An alternative name is *bypass capacitor* as it is used to bypass the power supply or other high impedance component of a circuit.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p02] Decoupling capacitors need not always be discrete components.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p02] Capacitors used in these applications may be built into a printed circuit board, between the various layers.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p02] These are often referred to as embedded capacitors.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p02] The layers in the board contributing to the capacitive properties also function as power and ground planes, and have a dielectric in between them, enabling them to operate as a parallel plate capacitor.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p02] When an inductive circuit is opened, the current through the inductance collapses quickly, creating a large voltage across the open circuit of the switch or relay.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p02] If the inductance is large enough, the energy may generate a spark, causing the contact points to oxidize, deteriorate, or sometimes weld together, or destroying a solid-state switch.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p02] A snubber capacitor across the newly opened circuit creates a path for this impulse to bypass the contact points, thereby preserving their life; these were commonly found in contact breaker ignition systems, for instance.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p02] Similarly, in smaller scale circuits, the spark may not be enough to damage the switch but may still radiate undesirable radio frequency interference (RFI), which a filter capacitor absorbs.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p02] Snubber capacitors are usually employed with a low-value resistor in series, to dissipate energy and minimize RFI.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p02] Such resistor-capacitor combinations are available in a single package.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p02] Capacitors are also used in parallel with interrupting units of a high-voltage circuit breaker to equally distribute the voltage between these units.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p02] In schematic diagrams, a capacitor used primarily for DC charge storage is often drawn vertically in circuit diagrams with the lower, more negative, plate drawn as an arc.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p02] The straight plate indicates the positive terminal of the device, if it is polarized (see electrolytic capacitor).
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p02] In single phase squirrel cage motors, the primary winding within the motor housing is not capable of starting a rotational motion on the rotor, but is capable of sustaining one.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p02] To start the motor, a secondary "start" winding has a series non-polarized *starting capacitor* to introduce a lead in the sinusoidal current.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p02] When the secondary (start) winding is placed at an angle with respect to the primary (run) winding, a rotating electric field is created.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p02] The force of the rotational field is not constant, but is sufficient to start the rotor spinning.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p02] When the rotor comes close to operating speed, a centrifugal switch (or current-sensitive relay in series with the main winding) disconnects the capacitor.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p02] The start capacitor is typically mounted to the side of the motor housing.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p02] These are called capacitor-start motors, that have relatively high starting torque.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p02] Typically they can have up-to four times as much starting torque as a split-phase motor and are used on applications such as compressors, pressure washers and any small device requiring high starting torques.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p02] Capacitor-run induction motors have a permanently connected phase-shifting capacitor in series with a second winding.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p02] The motor is much like a two-phase induction motor.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p02] Motor-starting capacitors are typically non-polarized electrolytic types, while running capacitors are conventional paper or plastic film dielectric types.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p02] The energy stored in a capacitor can be used to represent information, either in binary form, as in DRAMs, or in analogue form, as in analog sampled filters and CCDs.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p02] Capacitors can be used in analog circuits as components of integrators or more complex filters and in negative feedback loop stabilization.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p02] Signal processing circuits also use capacitors to integrate a current signal.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p02] Capacitors and inductors are applied together in tuned circuits to select information in particular frequency bands.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p02] For example, radio receivers rely on variable capacitors to tune the station frequency.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p02] Speakers use passive analog crossovers, and analog equalizers use capacitors to select different audio bands.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p02] The resonant frequency *f* of a tuned circuit is a function of the inductance (*L*) and capacitance (*C*) in series, and is given by: $f={\frac {1}{2\pi {\sqrt {LC}}}}$ where L is in henries and C is in farads.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p02] Most capacitors are designed to maintain a fixed physical structure.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p02] However, various factors can change the structure of the capacitor, and the resulting change in capacitance can be used to sense those factors.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p02] Capacitors with an exposed and porous dielectric can be used to measure humidity in air.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p02] ; as the fuel covers more of a pair of plates, the circuit capacitance increases.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p02] Squeezing the dielectric can change a capacitor at a few tens of bar pressure sufficiently that it can be used as a pressure sensor.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p02] A selected, but otherwise standard, polymer dielectric capacitor, when immersed in a compatible gas or liquid, can work usefully as a very low cost pressure sensor up to many hundreds of bar.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p02] Capacitors with a flexible plate can be used to measure strain or pressure.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p02] use pressure-sensing diaphragms, which form a capacitor plate of an oscillator circuit.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p02] , where one plate is moved by air pressure, relative to the fixed position of the other plate.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p02] capacitors etched on a chip to measure the magnitude and direction of the acceleration vector.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p02] deployment, and in many other applications.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p02] musical instrument by moving their hand since this changes the effective capacitance between the user's hand and the antenna.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p02] are used on many consumer electronic products.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p02] A capacitor can possess spring-like qualities in an oscillator circuit.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p02] In the image example, a capacitor acts to influence the biasing voltage at the npn transistor's base.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p02] The resistance values of the voltage-divider resistors and the capacitance value of the capacitor together control the oscillatory frequency.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p02] A light-emitting capacitor is made from a dielectric that uses phosphorescence to produce light.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p02] If one of the conductive plates is made with a transparent material, the light is visible.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p02] Light-emitting capacitors are used in the construction of electroluminescent panels, for applications such as backlighting for laptop computers.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p02] In this case, the entire panel is a capacitor used for the purpose of generating light.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p02] The hazards posed by a capacitor are usually determined by the amount of energy stored, which can cause electrical burns or heart fibrillation.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p02] Factors such as voltage and chassis material are of secondary consideration, which are more related to how easily a shock can be initiated rather than how much damage can occur.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p02] Shocks over ten joules generally damage skin, and are considered hazardous.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p02] Any capacitor that can store 50 joules or more is considered potentially lethal.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p02] Capacitors may retain a charge long after power is removed from a circuit; this charge can cause dangerous or fatal shocks or damage connected equipment.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p02] For example, the flash of a disposable camera has a photoflash capacitor that may contain over 15 joules of energy and be charged to over 300 volts.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p02] Service procedures for electronic devices usually include instructions to discharge large or high-voltage capacitors.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p02] Larger capacitors may have built-in discharge resistors to dissipate stored energy to a safe level within a few seconds after power is removed.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p02] High-voltage capacitors are stored with the terminals shorted, as protection from potentially dangerous voltages due to dielectric absorption or from transient voltages the capacitor may pick up from static charges or passing weather events.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p02] Some old, large oil-filled paper or plastic film capacitors contain polychlorinated biphenyls (PCBs) which can leak into groundwater from landfills.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p02] Capacitors containing PCBs were labelled as containing "Askarel" and several other trade names.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p02] PCB-filled paper capacitors are found in pre-1975 fluorescent lamp ballasts, and other applications.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p02] Such capacitors may be sealed in a metal can with ceramic feed-through connectors.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p02] Capacitors may catastrophically fail when subjected to voltages or currents beyond their rating, or in case of polarized capacitors, applied in a reverse polarity.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p02] Failures may create arcing that heats and vaporizes the dielectric fluid, causing a build up of pressurized gas that may result in swelling, rupture, or an explosion.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p02] Larger capacitors may have vents or similar mechanism to release of pressure in the event of failure.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p02] Capacitors used in RF or sustained high-current applications can overheat, especially in the center of the capacitor rolls.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p02] Capacitors used within high-energy capacitor banks can violently explode when a short in one capacitor causes sudden dumping of energy stored in the rest of the bank into the failing unit.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p02] High voltage vacuum capacitors can generate soft X-rays even during normal operation.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p02] Proper containment, fusing, and preventive maintenance can help to minimize these hazards.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p02] High-voltage capacitors may benefit from a pre-charge to limit in-rush currents at power-up of high voltage direct current (HVDC) circuits.
[src:dielectric-materials/capacitor-p02] This extends the life of the component and may mitigate high-voltage hazards.
[src:dielectric-materials/dielectric-strength] The theoretical dielectric strength of a material is an intrinsic property of the bulk material, and is independent of the configuration of the material or the electrodes with which the field is applied.
[src:dielectric-materials/dielectric-strength] This "intrinsic dielectric strength" corresponds to what would be measured using pure materials under ideal laboratory conditions.
[src:dielectric-materials/dielectric-strength] At breakdown, the electric field frees bound electrons.
[src:dielectric-materials/dielectric-strength] If the applied electric field is sufficiently high, free electrons from background radiation may be accelerated to velocities that can liberate additional electrons by collisions with neutral atoms or molecules, in a process known as avalanche breakdown.
[src:dielectric-materials/dielectric-strength] Breakdown occurs quite abruptly (typically in nanoseconds), resulting in the formation of an electrically conductive path and a disruptive discharge through the material.
[src:dielectric-materials/dielectric-strength] In a solid material, a breakdown event severely degrades, or even destroys, its insulating capability.
[src:dielectric-materials/dielectric-strength] Electric current is a flow of electrically charged particles in a material caused by an electric field.
[src:dielectric-materials/dielectric-strength] The mobile charged particles responsible for electric current are called charge carriers.
[src:dielectric-materials/dielectric-strength] In different substances different particles serve as charge carriers: in metals and other solids some of the outer electrons of each atom (conduction electrons) are able to move about the material; in electrolytes and plasma it is ions, electrically charged atoms or molecules, and electrons.
[src:dielectric-materials/dielectric-strength] A substance that has a high concentration of charge carriers available for conduction will conduct a large current with the given electric field created by a given voltage applied across it, and thus has a low electrical resistivity; this is called an electrical conductor.
[src:dielectric-materials/dielectric-strength] A material that has few charge carriers will conduct very little current with a given electric field and has a high resistivity; this is called an electrical insulator.
[src:dielectric-materials/dielectric-strength] However, when a large enough electric field is applied to any insulating substance, at a certain field strength the concentration of charge carriers in the material suddenly increases by many orders of magnitude, so its resistance drops and it becomes a conductor.
[src:dielectric-materials/dielectric-strength] The physical mechanism causing breakdown differs in different substances.
[src:dielectric-materials/dielectric-strength] In a solid, it usually occurs when the electric field becomes strong enough to pull outer valence electrons away from their atoms, so they become mobile.
[src:dielectric-materials/dielectric-strength] The field strength at which break down occurs is an intrinsic property of the material called its *dielectric strength*.
[src:dielectric-materials/dielectric-strength] In practical electric circuits electrical breakdown is often an unwanted occurrence, a failure of insulating material causing a short circuit, resulting in a catastrophic failure of the equipment.
[src:dielectric-materials/dielectric-strength] The sudden drop in resistance causes a high current to flow through the material, and the sudden extreme Joule heating may cause the material or other parts of the circuit to melt or vaporize explosively.
[src:dielectric-materials/dielectric-strength] However, breakdown itself is reversible.
[src:dielectric-materials/dielectric-strength] If the current supplied by the external circuit is sufficiently limited, no damage is done to the material, and reducing the applied voltage causes a transition back to the material's insulating state.
[src:dielectric-materials/dielectric-strength] The field strength at which break down occurs depends on the respective geometries of the dielectric (insulator) and the electrodes with which the electric field is applied, as well as the rate of increase of the applied electric field.
[src:dielectric-materials/dielectric-strength] Because dielectric materials usually contain minute defects, the practical dielectric strength will be a significantly less than the intrinsic dielectric strength of an ideal, defect-free, material.
[src:dielectric-materials/dielectric-strength] Dielectric films tend to exhibit greater dielectric strength than thicker samples of the same material.
[src:dielectric-materials/dielectric-strength] For instance, the dielectric strength of silicon dioxide films of thickness around 1 μm is about 0.5 GV/m.
[src:dielectric-materials/dielectric-strength] However very thin layers (below, say, 100 nm) become partially conductive because of electron tunneling.
[src:dielectric-materials/dielectric-strength] Multiple layers of thin dielectric films are used where maximum practical dielectric strength is required, such as high-voltage capacitors and pulse transformers.
[src:dielectric-materials/dielectric-strength] Since the dielectric strength of gases varies depending on the shape and configuration of the electrodes, it is usually measured as a fraction of the dielectric strength of nitrogen gas.
[src:dielectric-materials/dielectric-strength] In SI, the unit of dielectric strength is volts per meter (V/m).
[src:dielectric-materials/dielectric-strength] It is also common to see related units such as volt per centimeter (V/cm), megavolts per meter (MV/m), and so on.
[src:dielectric-materials/dielectric-strength] In United States customary units, dielectric strength is often specified in volt per mil (a mil is 1/1000 inch).
[src:dielectric-materials/dielectric] In electromagnetism, a **dielectric** (or **dielectric medium**) is an electrical insulator that can be polarised by an applied electric field.
[src:dielectric-materials/dielectric] Because of dielectric polarisation, positive charges are displaced in the direction of the field and negative charges shift in the direction opposite to the field.
[src:dielectric-materials/dielectric] This creates an internal electric field that reduces the overall field within the dielectric itself.
[src:dielectric-materials/dielectric] If a dielectric is composed of weakly bonded molecules, those molecules not only become polarised, but also reorient so that their symmetry axes align to the field.
[src:dielectric-materials/dielectric] The study of dielectric properties concerns storage and dissipation of electric and magnetic energy in materials.
[src:dielectric-materials/dielectric] Dielectrics are important for explaining various phenomena in electronics, optics, solid-state physics and cell biophysics.
[src:dielectric-materials/dielectric] Although the term *insulator* implies low electrical conduction, *dielectric* typically means materials with a high polarizability.
[src:dielectric-materials/dielectric] The latter is expressed by a number called the relative permittivity.
[src:dielectric-materials/dielectric] *Insulator* is generally used to indicate electrical obstruction while *dielectric* is used to indicate the energy storing capacity of the material (by means of polarisation).
[src:dielectric-materials/dielectric] A common example of a dielectric is the electrically insulating material between the metallic plates of a capacitor.
[src:dielectric-materials/dielectric] The polarisation of the dielectric by the applied electric field increases the capacitor's surface charge for the given electric field strength.
[src:dielectric-materials/dielectric] The term *dielectric* was coined by William Whewell (from *dia* + *electric*) in response to a request from Michael Faraday.
[src:dielectric-materials/dielectric] A *perfect dielectric* is a material with zero electrical conductivity (cf. perfect conductor infinite electrical conductivity), thus exhibiting only a displacement current; therefore it stores and returns electrical energy as if it were an ideal capacitor.
[src:dielectric-materials/dielectric] The electric susceptibility $\chi _{e}$ of a dielectric material is a measure of how easily it polarises in response to an electric field.
[src:dielectric-materials/dielectric] This, in turn, determines the electric permittivity of the material and thus influences many other phenomena in that medium, from the capacitance of capacitors to the speed of light.
[src:dielectric-materials/dielectric] where $\varepsilon _{0}$ is the electric permittivity of free space.
[src:dielectric-materials/dielectric] In general, a material cannot polarise instantaneously in response to an applied field.
[src:dielectric-materials/dielectric] That is, the polarisation is a convolution of the electric field at previous times with time-dependent susceptibility given by $\chi _{e}(\Delta t)$ .
[src:dielectric-materials/dielectric] The upper limit of this integral can be extended to infinity as well if one defines $\chi _{e}(\Delta t)=0$ for $\Delta t<0$ .
[src:dielectric-materials/dielectric] An instantaneous response corresponds to Dirac delta function susceptibility $\chi _{e}(\Delta t)=\chi _{e}\delta (\Delta t)$ .
[src:dielectric-materials/dielectric] It is more convenient in a linear system to take the Fourier transform and write this relationship as a function of frequency.
[src:dielectric-materials/dielectric] The susceptibility (or equivalently the permittivity) is frequency dependent.
[src:dielectric-materials/dielectric] The change of susceptibility with respect to frequency characterises the dispersion properties of the material.
[src:dielectric-materials/dielectric] Moreover, the fact that the polarisation can only depend on the electric field at previous times (i.e., $\chi _{e}(\Delta t)=0$ for $\Delta t<0$ ), a consequence of causality, imposes Kramers–Kronig constraints on the real and imaginary parts of the susceptibility $\chi _{e}(\omega )$ .
[src:dielectric-materials/dielectric] In the classical approach to the dielectric, the material is made up of atoms.
[src:dielectric-materials/dielectric] Each atom consists of a cloud of negative charge (electrons) bound to and surrounding a positive point charge at its center.
[src:dielectric-materials/dielectric] In the presence of an electric field, the charge cloud is distorted, as shown in the top right of the figure.
[src:dielectric-materials/dielectric] This can be reduced to a simple dipole using the superposition principle.
[src:dielectric-materials/dielectric] A dipole is characterised by its dipole moment, a vector quantity shown in the figure as the blue arrow labeled *M*.
[src:dielectric-materials/dielectric] It is the relationship between the electric field and the dipole moment that gives rise to the behaviour of the dielectric.
[src:dielectric-materials/dielectric] (Note that the dipole moment points in the same direction as the electric field in the figure.
[src:dielectric-materials/dielectric] When the electric field is removed, the atom returns to its original state.
[src:dielectric-materials/dielectric] The time required to do so is called relaxation time; an exponential decay.
[src:dielectric-materials/dielectric] This is the essence of the model in physics.
[src:dielectric-materials/dielectric] The behaviour of the dielectric now depends on the situation.
[src:dielectric-materials/dielectric] The more complicated the situation, the richer the model must be to accurately describe the behaviour.
[src:dielectric-materials/dielectric] When both the type of electric field and the type of material have been defined, one then chooses the simplest function *F* that correctly predicts the phenomena of interest.
[src:dielectric-materials/dielectric] Dipolar polarisation is a polarisation that is either inherent to polar molecules (orientation polarisation), or can be induced in any molecule in which the asymmetric distortion of the nuclei is possible (distortion polarisation).
[src:dielectric-materials/dielectric] Orientation polarisation results from a permanent dipole, e.g., that arises from the 104.45° angle between the asymmetric bonds between oxygen and hydrogen atoms in the water molecule, which retains polarisation in the absence of an external electric field.
[src:dielectric-materials/dielectric] The assembly of these dipoles forms a macroscopic polarisation.
[src:dielectric-materials/dielectric] When an external electric field is applied, the distance between charges within each permanent dipole, which is related to chemical bonding, remains constant in orientation polarisation; however, the direction of polarisation itself rotates.
[src:dielectric-materials/dielectric] This rotation occurs on a timescale that depends on the torque and surrounding local viscosity of the molecules.
[src:dielectric-materials/dielectric] Because the rotation is not instantaneous, dipolar polarisations lose the response to electric fields at the highest frequencies.
[src:dielectric-materials/dielectric] A molecule rotates about 1 radian per picosecond in a fluid, thus this loss occurs at about 1011 Hz (in the microwave region).
[src:dielectric-materials/dielectric] The delay of the response to the change of the electric field causes friction and heat.
[src:dielectric-materials/dielectric] When an external electric field is applied at infrared frequencies or less, the molecules are bent and stretched by the field and the molecular dipole moment changes.
[src:dielectric-materials/dielectric] The molecular vibration frequency is roughly the inverse of the time it takes for the molecules to bend, and this distortion polarisation disappears above the infrared.
[src:dielectric-materials/dielectric] Ionic polarisation is polarisation caused by relative displacements between positive and negative ions in ionic crystals (for example, NaCl).
[src:dielectric-materials/dielectric] If a crystal or molecule consists of atoms of more than one kind, the distribution of charges around an atom in the crystal or molecule leans to positive or negative.
[src:dielectric-materials/dielectric] As a result, when lattice vibrations or molecular vibrations induce relative displacements of the atoms, the centers of positive and negative charges are also displaced.
[src:dielectric-materials/dielectric] The locations of these centers are affected by the symmetry of the displacements.
[src:dielectric-materials/dielectric] When the centers do not correspond, polarisation arises in molecules or crystals.
[src:dielectric-materials/dielectric] This polarisation is called **ionic polarisation**.
[src:dielectric-materials/dielectric] Ionic polarisation causes the ferroelectric effect as well as dipolar polarisation.
[src:dielectric-materials/dielectric] The ferroelectric transition, which is caused by the lining up of the orientations of permanent dipoles along a particular direction, is called an **order-disorder phase transition**.
[src:dielectric-materials/dielectric] The transition caused by ionic polarisations in crystals is called a **displacive phase transition**.
[src:dielectric-materials/dielectric] Ionic polarisation enables the production of energy-rich compounds in cells (the proton pump in mitochondria) and, at the plasma membrane, the establishment of the resting potential, energetically unfavourable transport of ions, and cell-to-cell communication (the Na+/K+-ATPase).
[src:dielectric-materials/dielectric] All cells in animal body tissues are electrically polarised – in other words, they maintain a voltage difference across the cell's plasma membrane, known as the membrane potential.
[src:dielectric-materials/dielectric] This electrical polarisation results from a complex interplay between ion transporters and ion channels.
[src:dielectric-materials/dielectric] In neurons, the types of ion channels in the membrane usually vary across different parts of the cell, giving the dendrites, axon, and cell body different electrical properties.
[src:dielectric-materials/dielectric] As a result, some parts of the membrane of a neuron may be excitable (capable of generating action potentials), whereas others are not.
[src:dielectric-materials/dielectric] In physics, **dielectric dispersion** is the dependence of the permittivity of a dielectric material on the frequency of an applied electric field.
[src:dielectric-materials/dielectric] Because there is a lag between changes in polarisation and changes in the electric field, the permittivity of the dielectric is a complex function of the frequency of the electric field.
[src:dielectric-materials/dielectric] Dielectric dispersion is very important for the applications of dielectric materials and the analysis of polarisation systems.
[src:dielectric-materials/dielectric] This is one instance of a general phenomenon known as material dispersion: a frequency-dependent response of a medium for wave propagation.
[src:dielectric-materials/dielectric] The electronic polarisation loses its response in the ultraviolet region around 1015 Hz.
[src:dielectric-materials/dielectric] In the frequency region above ultraviolet, permittivity approaches the constant *ε*0 in every substance, where *ε*0 is the permittivity of the free space.
[src:dielectric-materials/dielectric] Because permittivity indicates the strength of the relation between an electric field and polarisation, if a polarisation process loses its response, permittivity decreases.
[src:dielectric-materials/dielectric] In physics, **dielectric relaxation** refers to the relaxation response of a dielectric medium to an external, oscillating electric field.
[src:dielectric-materials/dielectric] This relaxation is often described in terms of permittivity as a function of frequency, which can, for ideal systems, be described by the Debye equation.
[src:dielectric-materials/dielectric] On the other hand, the distortion related to ionic and electronic polarisation shows behaviour of the resonance or oscillator type.
[src:dielectric-materials/dielectric] The character of the distortion process depends on the structure, composition, and surroundings of the sample.
[src:dielectric-materials/dielectric] where *ε∞* is the permittivity at the high frequency limit, Δ*ε* = *εs* − *ε∞* where *εs* is the static, low frequency permittivity, and *τ* is the characteristic relaxation time of the medium.
[src:dielectric-materials/dielectric] In the former convention, the functions $\varepsilon '$ and $\varepsilon ''$ representing real and imaginary parts are given by ${\hat {\varepsilon }}(\omega )=\varepsilon '+i\varepsilon ''$ whereas in the latter convention ${\hat {\varepsilon }}(\omega )=\varepsilon '-i\varepsilon ''$ .
[src:dielectric-materials/dielectric] The above equation uses the latter convention.
[src:dielectric-materials/dielectric] This relaxation model was introduced by and named after the physicist Peter Debye (1913).
[src:dielectric-materials/dielectric] It is characteristic for dynamic polarisation with only one relaxation time.
[src:dielectric-materials/dielectric] This equation is used when the dielectric loss peak shows symmetric broadening.
[src:dielectric-materials/dielectric] This equation is used when the dielectric loss peak shows asymmetric broadening.
[src:dielectric-materials/dielectric] This equation considers both symmetric and asymmetric broadening.
[src:dielectric-materials/dielectric] This shows the response of dielectrics to an applied DC field to behave according to a power law, which can be expressed as an integral over weighted exponential functions.
[src:dielectric-materials/dielectric] This is used when the dielectric loss is approximately constant for a wide range of frequencies.
[src:dielectric-materials/dielectric] Paraelectricity is the nominal behaviour of dielectrics when the dielectric permittivity tensor is proportional to the unit matrix, i.e., an applied electric field causes polarisation and/or alignment of dipoles only parallel to the applied electric field.
[src:dielectric-materials/dielectric] Contrary to the analogy with a paramagnetic material, no permanent electric dipole needs to exist in a paraelectric material.
[src:dielectric-materials/dielectric] Removal of the fields results in the dipolar polarisation returning to zero.
[src:dielectric-materials/dielectric] The mechanisms that causes **paraelectric** behaviour are distortion of individual ions (displacement of the electron cloud from the nucleus) and polarisation of molecules or combinations of ions or defects.
[src:dielectric-materials/dielectric] Paraelectricity can occur in crystal phases where electric dipoles are unaligned and thus have the potential to align in an external electric field and weaken it.
[src:dielectric-materials/dielectric] Most dielectric materials are paraelectrics.
[src:dielectric-materials/dielectric] A specific example of a paraelectric material of high dielectric constant is strontium titanate.
[src:dielectric-materials/dielectric] The LiNbO3 crystal is ferroelectric below 1430 K, and above this temperature it transforms into a disordered paraelectric phase.
[src:dielectric-materials/dielectric] Similarly, other perovskites also exhibit paraelectricity at high temperatures.
[src:dielectric-materials/dielectric] Paraelectricity has been explored as a possible refrigeration mechanism; polarising a paraelectric by applying an electric field under adiabatic process conditions raises the temperature, while removing the field lowers the temperature.
[src:dielectric-materials/dielectric] A heat pump that operates by polarising the paraelectric, allowing it to return to ambient temperature (by dissipating the extra heat), bringing it into contact with the object to be cooled, and finally depolarising it, would result in refrigeration.
[src:dielectric-materials/dielectric] Generally, strontium titanate (SrTiO 3) is used for devices operating at low temperatures, while barium strontium titanate (Ba 1−xSr xTiO 3) substitutes for room temperature devices.
[src:dielectric-materials/dielectric] Other potential materials include microwave dielectrics and carbon nanotube (CNT) composites.
[src:dielectric-materials/dielectric] In 2013, multi-sheet layers of strontium titanate interleaved with single layers of strontium oxide produced a dielectric capable of operating at up to 125 GHz.
[src:dielectric-materials/dielectric] The material was created via molecular beam epitaxy.
[src:dielectric-materials/dielectric] The two have mismatched crystal spacing that produces strain within the strontium titanate layer that makes it less stable and tunable.
[src:dielectric-materials/dielectric] Systems such as Ba 1−xSr xTiO 3 have a paraelectric–ferroelectric transition just below ambient temperature, providing high tunability.
[src:dielectric-materials/dielectric] Films suffer significant losses arising from defects.
[src:dielectric-materials/dielectric] Commercially manufactured capacitors typically use a solid dielectric material with high permittivity as the intervening medium between the stored positive and negative charges.
[src:dielectric-materials/dielectric] This material is often referred to in technical contexts as the *capacitor dielectric*.
[src:dielectric-materials/dielectric] The most obvious advantage to using such a dielectric material is that it prevents the conducting plates, on which the charges are stored, from coming into direct electrical contact.
[src:dielectric-materials/dielectric] More significantly, however, a high permittivity allows a greater stored charge at a given voltage.
[src:dielectric-materials/dielectric] This can be seen by treating the case of a linear dielectric with permittivity *ε* and thickness *d* between two conducting plates with uniform charge density *σε*.
[src:dielectric-materials/dielectric] From this, it can easily be seen that a larger *ε* leads to greater charge stored and thus greater capacitance.
[src:dielectric-materials/dielectric] Dielectric materials used for capacitors are also chosen such that they are resistant to ionisation.
[src:dielectric-materials/dielectric] This allows the capacitor to operate at higher voltages before the insulating dielectric ionises and begins to allow undesirable current.
[src:dielectric-materials/dielectric] A *dielectric resonator oscillator* (DRO) is an electronic component that exhibits resonance of the polarisation response for a narrow range of frequencies, generally in the microwave band.
[src:dielectric-materials/dielectric] It consists of a "puck" of ceramic that has a large dielectric constant and a low dissipation factor.
[src:dielectric-materials/dielectric] Such resonators are often used to provide a frequency reference in an oscillator circuit.
[src:dielectric-materials/dielectric] An unshielded dielectric resonator can be used as a dielectric resonator antenna (DRA).
[src:dielectric-materials/dielectric] From 2002 to 2004, the United States Army Research Laboratory (ARL) conducted research on thin film technology.
[src:dielectric-materials/dielectric] Barium strontium titanate (BST), a ferroelectric thin film, was studied for the fabrication of radio frequency and microwave components, such as voltage-controlled oscillators, tunable filters and phase shifters.
[src:dielectric-materials/dielectric] The research was part of an effort to provide the Army with highly-tunable, microwave-compatible materials for broadband electric-field tunable devices, which operate consistently in extreme temperatures.
[src:dielectric-materials/dielectric] This work improved tunability of bulk barium strontium titanate, which is a thin film enabler for electronics components.
[src:dielectric-materials/dielectric] ARL researchers explored how small concentrations of acceptor dopants can dramatically modify the properties of ferroelectric materials such as BST.
[src:dielectric-materials/dielectric] Researchers "doped" BST thin films with magnesium, analyzing the "structure, microstructure, surface morphology and film/substrate compositional quality" of the result.
[src:dielectric-materials/dielectric] The Mg doped BST films showed "improved dielectric properties, low leakage current, and good tunability", meriting potential for use in microwave tunable devices.
[src:dielectric-materials/dielectric] Dielectric materials can be solids, liquids, or gases.
[src:dielectric-materials/dielectric] Solid dielectrics are perhaps the most commonly used dielectrics in electrical engineering, and many solids are very good insulators.
[src:dielectric-materials/dielectric] Some examples include porcelain, glass, and most plastics.
[src:dielectric-materials/dielectric] Air, nitrogen and sulfur hexafluoride are the three most commonly used gaseous dielectrics.
[src:dielectric-materials/ferroelectricity] In physics and materials science, **ferroelectricity** is the property of certain materials that exhibit a spontaneous electric polarization—an internal electric alignment that arises naturally without an external source.
[src:dielectric-materials/ferroelectricity] This polarization can be reversed when an external electric field is applied.
[src:dielectric-materials/ferroelectricity] All ferroelectric materials are also piezoelectric (they generate an electric charge when mechanically stressed) and pyroelectric (they generate a charge when heated or cooled).
[src:dielectric-materials/ferroelectricity] Their distinctive feature is that the natural electrical polarization is reversible.
[src:dielectric-materials/ferroelectricity] The term ferroelectricity was coined in analogy to ferromagnetism, where a material exhibits a permanent magnetic moment.
[src:dielectric-materials/ferroelectricity] Ferromagnetism was already well established when ferroelectricity was first observed in 1920 in Rochelle salt by American physicist Joseph Valasek.
[src:dielectric-materials/ferroelectricity] The prefix ferro (meaning iron) was adopted even though most ferroelectric materials do not contain iron.
[src:dielectric-materials/ferroelectricity] Materials that are both ferroelectric and ferromagnetic are known as multiferroics, and they are of particular interest because they combine electric and magnetic ordering in a single system.
[src:dielectric-materials/ferroelectricity] When most materials are electrically polarized, the induced polarization *P*, is almost exactly proportional to the applied external electric field *E*; so the polarization is a linear function.
[src:dielectric-materials/ferroelectricity] This is called linear dielectric polarization (see figure).
[src:dielectric-materials/ferroelectricity] Some materials, known as paraelectric materials, show a more enhanced nonlinear polarization (see figure).
[src:dielectric-materials/ferroelectricity] The electric permittivity, corresponding to the slope of the polarization curve, is not constant as in linear dielectrics but is a function of the external electric field.
[src:dielectric-materials/ferroelectricity] In addition to being nonlinear, ferroelectric materials demonstrate a spontaneous nonzero polarization (after entrainment, see figure) even when the applied field *E* is zero.
[src:dielectric-materials/ferroelectricity] They are called ferroelectrics by analogy to ferromagnetic materials, which have spontaneous magnetization and exhibit similar hysteresis loops.
[src:dielectric-materials/ferroelectricity] Typically, materials demonstrate ferroelectricity only below a certain phase transition temperature, called the Curie temperature (*T*C) and are paraelectric above this temperature: the spontaneous polarization vanishes, and the ferroelectric crystal transforms into the paraelectric state.
[src:dielectric-materials/ferroelectricity] Many ferroelectrics lose their pyroelectric properties above *T*C completely, because their paraelectric phase has a centrosymmetric crystal structure.
[src:dielectric-materials/ferroelectricity] The nonlinear nature of ferroelectric materials can be used to make capacitors with adjustable capacitance.
[src:dielectric-materials/ferroelectricity] Typically, a ferroelectric capacitor simply consists of a pair of electrodes sandwiching a layer of ferroelectric material.
[src:dielectric-materials/ferroelectricity] The permittivity of ferroelectrics is not only adjustable but commonly also very high, especially when close to the phase transition temperature.
[src:dielectric-materials/ferroelectricity] Because of this, ferroelectric capacitors are small in physical size compared to dielectric (non-tunable) capacitors of similar capacitance.
[src:dielectric-materials/ferroelectricity] The spontaneous polarization of ferroelectric materials implies a hysteresis effect which can be used as a memory function, and ferroelectric capacitors are indeed used to make ferroelectric RAM for computers and RFID cards.
[src:dielectric-materials/ferroelectricity] In these applications thin films of ferroelectric materials are typically used, as this allows the field required to switch the polarization to be achieved with a moderate voltage.
[src:dielectric-materials/ferroelectricity] However, when using thin films a great deal of attention needs to be paid to the interfaces, electrodes and sample quality for devices to work reliably.
[src:dielectric-materials/ferroelectricity] Ferroelectric materials are required by symmetry considerations to also be piezoelectric and pyroelectric.
[src:dielectric-materials/ferroelectricity] The combined properties of memory, piezoelectricity, and pyroelectricity make ferroelectric capacitors very useful, e.g. for sensor applications.
[src:dielectric-materials/ferroelectricity] Another idea of recent interest is the *ferroelectric tunnel junction* (*FTJ*) in which a contact is made up by nanometer-thick ferroelectric film placed between metal electrodes.
[src:dielectric-materials/ferroelectricity] The thickness of the ferroelectric layer is small enough to allow tunneling of electrons.
[src:dielectric-materials/ferroelectricity] The piezoelectric and interface effects as well as the depolarization field may lead to a giant electroresistance (GER) switching effect.
[src:dielectric-materials/ferroelectricity] Yet another burgeoning application is multiferroics, where researchers are looking for ways to couple magnetic and ferroelectric ordering within a material or heterostructure; there are several recent reviews on this topic.
[src:dielectric-materials/ferroelectricity] Catalytic properties of ferroelectrics have been studied since 1952 when Parravano observed anomalies in CO oxidation rates over ferroelectric sodium and potassium niobates near the Curie temperature of these materials.
[src:dielectric-materials/ferroelectricity] Surface-perpendicular component of the ferroelectric polarization can dope polarization-dependent charges on surfaces of ferroelectric materials, changing their chemistry.
[src:dielectric-materials/ferroelectricity] This opens the possibility of performing catalysis beyond the limits of the Sabatier principle.
[src:dielectric-materials/ferroelectricity] Sabatier principle states that the surface-adsorbates interaction has to be an optimal amount: not too weak to be inert toward the reactants and not too strong to poison the surface and avoid desorption of the products: a compromise situation.
[src:dielectric-materials/ferroelectricity] This set of optimum interactions is usually referred to as "top of the volcano" in activity volcano plots.
[src:dielectric-materials/ferroelectricity] On the other hand, ferroelectric polarization-dependent chemistry can offer the possibility of switching the surface—adsorbates interaction from strong adsorption to strong desorption, thus a compromise between desorption and adsorption is no longer needed.
[src:dielectric-materials/ferroelectricity] Ferroelectric polarization can also act as an energy harvester.
[src:dielectric-materials/ferroelectricity] Polarization can help the separation of photo-generated electron-hole pairs, leading to enhanced photocatalysis.
[src:dielectric-materials/ferroelectricity] Also, due to pyroelectric and piezoelectric effects under varying temperature (heating/cooling cycles) or varying strain (vibrations) conditions extra charges can appear on the surface and drive various (electro)chemical reactions forward.
[src:dielectric-materials/ferroelectricity] Photoferroelectric imaging is a technique to record optical information on pieces of ferroelectric material.
[src:dielectric-materials/ferroelectricity] The images are nonvolatile and selectively erasable.
[src:dielectric-materials/ferroelectricity] The internal electric dipoles of a ferroelectric material are coupled to the material lattice so anything that changes the lattice will change the strength of the dipoles (in other words, a change in the spontaneous polarization).
[src:dielectric-materials/ferroelectricity] The change in the spontaneous polarization results in a change in the surface charge.
[src:dielectric-materials/ferroelectricity] This can cause current flow in the case of a ferroelectric capacitor even without the presence of an external voltage across the capacitor.
[src:dielectric-materials/ferroelectricity] Two stimuli that will change the lattice dimensions of a material are force and temperature.
[src:dielectric-materials/ferroelectricity] The generation of a surface charge in response to the application of an external stress to a material is called piezoelectricity.
[src:dielectric-materials/ferroelectricity] A change in the spontaneous polarization of a material in response to a change in temperature is called pyroelectricity.
[src:dielectric-materials/ferroelectricity] Generally, there are 230 space groups among which 32 crystalline classes can be found in crystals.
[src:dielectric-materials/ferroelectricity] There are 21 non-centrosymmetric classes, within which 20 are piezoelectric.
[src:dielectric-materials/ferroelectricity] Among the piezoelectric classes, 10 have a spontaneous electric polarization which varies with temperature; thus they are pyroelectric.
[src:dielectric-materials/ferroelectricity] Ferroelectricity is a subset of pyroelectricity, which brings spontaneous electronic polarization to the material.
[src:dielectric-materials/ferroelectricity] Ferroelectric phase transitions are often characterized as either displacive (such as BaTiO3) or order-disorder (such as NaNO2), though often phase transitions will demonstrate elements of both behaviors.
[src:dielectric-materials/ferroelectricity] This leads to an asymmetrical shift in the equilibrium ion positions and hence to a permanent dipole moment.
[src:dielectric-materials/ferroelectricity] The ionic displacement in barium titanate concerns the relative position of the titanium ion within the oxygen octahedral cage.
[src:dielectric-materials/ferroelectricity] In lead titanate, another key ferroelectric material, although the structure is rather similar to barium titanate the driving force for ferroelectricity is more complex with interactions between the lead and oxygen ions also playing an important role.
[src:dielectric-materials/ferroelectricity] In an order-disorder ferroelectric, there is a dipole moment in each unit cell, but at high temperatures they are pointing in random directions.
[src:dielectric-materials/ferroelectricity] Upon lowering the temperature and going through the phase transition, the dipoles order, all pointing in the same direction within a domain.
[src:dielectric-materials/ferroelectricity] An important ferroelectric material for applications is lead zirconate titanate (PZT), which is part of the solid solution formed between ferroelectric lead titanate and anti-ferroelectric lead zirconate.
[src:dielectric-materials/ferroelectricity] Ferroelectric crystals often show several transition temperatures and domain structure hysteresis, much as do ferromagnetic crystals.
[src:dielectric-materials/ferroelectricity] The nature of the phase transition in some ferroelectric crystals is still not well understood.
[src:dielectric-materials/ferroelectricity] Meyer used symmetry arguments to predict ferroelectric liquid crystals, and the prediction could immediately be verified by several observations of behavior connected to ferroelectricity in smectic liquid-crystal phases that are chiral and tilted.
[src:dielectric-materials/ferroelectricity] The technology allows the building of flat-screen monitors.
[src:dielectric-materials/ferroelectricity] Mass production between 1994 and 1999 was carried out by Canon.
[src:dielectric-materials/ferroelectricity] Ferroelectric liquid crystals are used in production of reflective LCoS.
[src:dielectric-materials/ferroelectricity] In 2010 David Field found that prosaic films of chemicals such as nitrous oxide or propane exhibited ferroelectric properties.
[src:dielectric-materials/ferroelectricity] This new class of ferroelectric materials exhibit "spontelectric" properties, and may have wide-ranging applications in device and nano-technology and also influence the electrical nature of dust in the interstellar medium.
[src:dielectric-materials/ferroelectricity] Other ferroelectric materials used include triglycine sulfate, polyvinylidene fluoride (PVDF) and lithium tantalate.
[src:dielectric-materials/ferroelectricity] A single atom thick ferroelectric monolayer can be created using pure bismuth.
[src:dielectric-materials/ferroelectricity] It should be possible to produce materials which combine both ferroelectric and metallic properties simultaneously, at room temperature.
[src:dielectric-materials/ferroelectricity] According to research published in 2018 in *Nature Communications*, scientists were able to produce a two-dimensional sheet of material which was both ferroelectric (had a polar crystal structure) and which conducted electricity.
[src:dielectric-materials/ferroelectricity] An introduction to Landau theory can be found here.
[src:dielectric-materials/ferroelectricity] Based on Ginzburg–Landau theory, the free energy of a ferroelectric material, in the absence of an electric field and applied stress may be written as a Taylor expansion in terms of the order parameter, P.
[src:dielectric-materials/ferroelectricity] If a sixth order expansion is used (i.e.
[src:dielectric-materials/ferroelectricity] where *Px*, *Py*, *Pz* are the components of the polarization vector in the *x*, *y*, *z* directions respectively, and the coefficients, *αi*, *αij*, *αijk* must be consistent with the crystal symmetry.
[src:dielectric-materials/ferroelectricity] To investigate domain formation and other phenomena in ferroelectrics, these equations are often used in the context of a phase field model.
[src:dielectric-materials/ferroelectricity] Typically, this involves adding a gradient term, an electrostatic term and an elastic term to the free energy.
[src:dielectric-materials/ferroelectricity] The equations are then discretized onto a grid using the finite difference method or finite element method and solved subject to the constraints of Gauss's law and Linear elasticity.
[src:dielectric-materials/ferroelectricity] In all known ferroelectrics, *α*0 > 0 and *α*111 > 0.
[src:dielectric-materials/ferroelectricity] These coefficients may be obtained experimentally or from ab-initio simulations.
[src:dielectric-materials/ferroelectricity] For ferroelectrics with a first order phase transition, *α*11 < 0, whereas *α*11 > 0 for a second order phase transition.
[src:dielectric-materials/ferroelectricity] This free energy has the shape of a double well potential with two free energy minima at *Px* = *Ps*, the spontaneous polarization.
[src:dielectric-materials/ferroelectricity] Plotting Ex (on the X axis) as a function of Pe (but on the Y axis) gives an S-shaped curve which is multi-valued in Pe for some values of Ex.
[src:dielectric-materials/ferroelectricity] The central part of the 'S' corresponds to a free energy local maximum (since ${\tfrac {\partial ^{2}\Delta E}{\partial P_{x}^{2}}}<0$ ).
[src:dielectric-materials/ferroelectricity] Elimination of this region, and connection of the top and bottom portions of the 'S' curve by vertical lines at the discontinuities gives the hysteresis loop of internal polarization due to an external electric field.
[src:dielectric-materials/ferroelectricity] Sliding ferroelectricity is widely found but only in two-dimensional (2D) van der Waals stacked layers.
[src:dielectric-materials/ferroelectricity] The vertical electric polarization is switched by in-plane interlayer sliding.
[src:dielectric-materials/permittivity] In electromagnetism, the **absolute permittivity**, often simply called **permittivity** and denoted by the Greek letter ε (epsilon), is a measure of the electric polarizability of a dielectric material.
[src:dielectric-materials/permittivity] A material with high permittivity polarizes more in response to an applied electric field than a material with low permittivity, thereby storing more energy in the material.
[src:dielectric-materials/permittivity] In electrostatics, the permittivity plays an important role in determining the capacitance of a capacitor.
[src:dielectric-materials/permittivity] More generally, the permittivity is a thermodynamic function of state.
[src:dielectric-materials/permittivity] It can depend on the frequency, magnitude, and direction of the applied field.
[src:dielectric-materials/permittivity] The SI unit for permittivity is farad per meter (F/m).
[src:dielectric-materials/permittivity] This dimensionless quantity is also often and ambiguously referred to as the *permittivity*.
[src:dielectric-materials/permittivity] Another common term encountered for both absolute and relative permittivity is the *dielectric constant* which has been deprecated in physics and engineering as well as in chemistry.
[src:dielectric-materials/permittivity] By definition, a perfect vacuum has a relative permittivity of exactly 1 whereas at standard temperature and pressure, air has a relative permittivity of εr air ≡ κair ≈ 1.0006 .
[src:dielectric-materials/permittivity] The term "permittivity" was introduced in the 1880s by Oliver Heaviside to complement Thomson's (1872) "permeability".
[src:dielectric-materials/permittivity] Formerly written as p, the designation with ε has been in common use since the 1950s.
[src:dielectric-materials/permittivity] The SI unit of permittivity is farad per meter (F/m or F·m−1).
[src:dielectric-materials/permittivity] In electromagnetism, the electric displacement field **D** represents the distribution of electric charges in a given medium resulting from the presence of an electric field **E**.
[src:dielectric-materials/permittivity] This distribution includes charge migration and electric dipole reorientation.
[src:dielectric-materials/permittivity] If the medium is anisotropic, the permittivity is a second rank tensor.
[src:dielectric-materials/permittivity] In general, permittivity is not a constant, as it can vary with the position in the medium, the frequency of the field applied, humidity, temperature, and other parameters.
[src:dielectric-materials/permittivity] In a nonlinear medium, the permittivity can depend on the strength of the electric field.
[src:dielectric-materials/permittivity] Permittivity as a function of frequency can take on real or complex values.
[src:dielectric-materials/permittivity] In SI units, permittivity is measured in farads per meter (F/m or A2·s4·kg−1·m−3).
[src:dielectric-materials/permittivity] The displacement field **D** is measured in units of coulombs per square meter (C/m2), while the electric field **E** is measured in volts per meter (V/m).
[src:dielectric-materials/permittivity] **D** and **E** describe the interaction between charged objects.
[src:dielectric-materials/permittivity] **D** is related to the *charge densities* associated with this interaction, while **E** is related to the *forces* and *potential differences*.
[src:dielectric-materials/permittivity] The vacuum permittivity εo (also called **permittivity of free space** or the **electric constant**) is the ratio ⁠*D*/*E*⁠ in free space.
[src:dielectric-materials/permittivity] The constants c and µ0 were both defined in SI units to have exact numerical values until the 2019 revision of the SI.
[src:dielectric-materials/permittivity] In contrast, the ampere was a measured quantity before 2019, but since then the ampere is now exactly defined and it is μ0 that is an experimentally measured quantity (with consequent uncertainty) and therefore so is the new 2019 definition of ε0 (c remains exactly defined before and since 2019).
[src:dielectric-materials/permittivity] The linear permittivity of a homogeneous material is usually given relative to that of free space, as a relative permittivity εr (also called dielectric constant, although this term is deprecated and sometimes only refers to the static, zero-frequency relative permittivity).
[src:dielectric-materials/permittivity] In an anisotropic material, the relative permittivity may be a tensor, causing birefringence.
[src:dielectric-materials/permittivity] where χ (frequently written χe) is the electric susceptibility of the material.
[src:dielectric-materials/permittivity] where εo is the electric permittivity of free space.
[src:dielectric-materials/permittivity] The susceptibility is also related to the polarizability of individual particles in the medium by the Clausius-Mossotti relation.
[src:dielectric-materials/permittivity] The capacitance of a capacitor is based on its design and architecture, meaning it will not change with charging and discharging.
[src:dielectric-materials/permittivity] where A is the area of one plate, d is the distance between the plates, and $\varepsilon$ is the permittivity of the medium between the two plates.
[src:dielectric-materials/permittivity] Permittivity is connected to electric flux (and by extension electric field) through Gauss's law.
[src:dielectric-materials/permittivity] $E\ A\ \cos \theta ={\frac {\;Q_{\text{enc}}}{\ \varepsilon _{0}\ }}\ ,$ where $\ \theta \$ represents the angle between the electric field lines and the normal (perpendicular) to S.
[src:dielectric-materials/permittivity] This formula applies to the electric field due to a point charge, outside of a conducting sphere or shell, outside of a uniformly charged insulating sphere, or between the plates of a spherical capacitor.
[src:dielectric-materials/permittivity] That is, the polarization is a convolution of the electric field at previous times with time-dependent susceptibility given by *χ*(Δ*t*).
[src:dielectric-materials/permittivity] The upper limit of this integral can be extended to infinity as well if one defines *χ*(Δ*t*) = 0 for Δ*t* < 0.
[src:dielectric-materials/permittivity] An instantaneous response would correspond to a Dirac delta function susceptibility *χ*(Δ*t*) = *χδ*(Δ*t*).
[src:dielectric-materials/permittivity] It is convenient to take the Fourier transform with respect to time and write this relationship as a function of frequency.
[src:dielectric-materials/permittivity] This frequency dependence of the susceptibility leads to frequency dependence of the permittivity.
[src:dielectric-materials/permittivity] The shape of the susceptibility with respect to frequency characterizes the dispersion properties of the material.
[src:dielectric-materials/permittivity] Moreover, the fact that the polarization can only depend on the electric field at previous times (i.e. effectively *χ*(Δ*t*) = 0 for Δ*t* < 0), a consequence of causality, imposes Kramers–Kronig constraints on the susceptibility *χ*(0).
[src:dielectric-materials/permittivity] As opposed to the response of a vacuum, the response of normal materials to external fields generally depends on the frequency of the field.
[src:dielectric-materials/permittivity] This frequency dependence reflects the fact that a material's polarization does not change instantaneously when an electric field is applied.
[src:dielectric-materials/permittivity] The response must always be *causal* (arising after the applied field), which can be represented by a phase difference.
[src:dielectric-materials/permittivity] (since complex numbers allow specification of magnitude and phase).
[src:dielectric-materials/permittivity] At the high-frequency limit (meaning optical frequencies), the complex permittivity is commonly referred to as ε∞ (or sometimes εopt).
[src:dielectric-materials/permittivity] At the plasma frequency and below, dielectrics behave as ideal metals, with electron gas behavior.
[src:dielectric-materials/permittivity] The static permittivity is a good approximation for alternating fields of low frequencies, and as the frequency increases a measurable phase difference δ emerges between **D** and **E**.
[src:dielectric-materials/permittivity] The frequency at which the phase shift becomes noticeable depends on temperature and the details of the medium.
[src:dielectric-materials/permittivity] The choice of sign for time-dependence, e−*iωt*, dictates the sign convention for the imaginary part of permittivity.
[src:dielectric-materials/permittivity] The complex permittivity is usually a complicated function of frequency ω, since it is a superimposed description of dispersion phenomena occurring at multiple frequencies.
[src:dielectric-materials/permittivity] The dielectric function *ε*(*ω*) must have poles only for frequencies with positive imaginary parts, and therefore satisfies the Kramers–Kronig relations.
[src:dielectric-materials/permittivity] However, in the narrow frequency ranges that are often studied in practice, the permittivity can be approximated as frequency-independent or by model functions.
[src:dielectric-materials/permittivity] At a given frequency, ε″, leads to absorption loss if it is positive (in the above sign convention) and gain if it is negative.
[src:dielectric-materials/permittivity] More generally, the imaginary parts of the eigenvalues of the anisotropic dielectric tensor should be considered.
[src:dielectric-materials/permittivity] In the case of solids, the complex dielectric function is intimately connected to band structure.
[src:dielectric-materials/permittivity] The primary quantity that characterizes the electronic structure of any crystalline material is the probability of photon absorption, which is directly related to the imaginary part of the optical dielectric function *ε*(*ω*).
[src:dielectric-materials/permittivity] In this expression, *W**c*,*v*(*E*) represents the product of the Brillouin zone-averaged transition probability at the energy E with the joint density of states, *J**c*,*v*(*E*); φ is a broadening function, representing the role of scattering in smearing out the energy levels.
[src:dielectric-materials/permittivity] In general, the broadening is intermediate between Lorentzian and Gaussian; for an alloy it is somewhat closer to Gaussian because of strong scattering from statistical fluctuations in the local composition on a nanometer scale.
[src:dielectric-materials/permittivity] If ε2 vanishes, then the tensor is diagonal but not proportional to the identity and the medium is said to be a uniaxial medium, which has similar properties to a uniaxial crystal.
[src:dielectric-materials/permittivity] Materials can be classified according to their complex-valued permittivity ε, upon comparison of its real *ε*′ and imaginary *ε*″ components (or, equivalently, conductivity, σ, when accounted for in the latter).
[src:dielectric-materials/permittivity] Those materials that do not fall under either limit are considered to be general media.
[src:dielectric-materials/permittivity] Note that this is using the electrical engineering convention of the complex conjugate ambiguity; the physics/chemistry convention involves the complex conjugate of these equations.
[src:dielectric-materials/permittivity] The size of the displacement current is dependent on the frequency ω of the applied field E; there is no displacement current in a constant field.
[src:dielectric-materials/permittivity] The above effects often combine to cause non-linear effects within capacitors.
[src:dielectric-materials/permittivity] For example, dielectric absorption refers to the inability of a capacitor that has been charged for a long time to completely discharge when briefly discharged.
[src:dielectric-materials/permittivity] Although an ideal capacitor would remain at zero volts after being discharged, real capacitors will develop a small voltage, a phenomenon that is also called *soakage* or *battery action*.
[src:dielectric-materials/permittivity] For some dielectrics, such as many polymer films, the resulting voltage may be less than 1–2% of the original voltage.
[src:dielectric-materials/permittivity] However, it can be as much as 15–25% in the case of electrolytic capacitors or supercapacitors.
[src:dielectric-materials/permittivity] In terms of quantum mechanics, permittivity is explained by atomic and molecular interactions.
[src:dielectric-materials/permittivity] At low frequencies, molecules in polar dielectrics are polarized by an applied electric field, which induces periodic rotations.
[src:dielectric-materials/permittivity] For example, at the microwave frequency, the microwave field causes the periodic rotation of water molecules, sufficient to break hydrogen bonds.
[src:dielectric-materials/permittivity] The field does work against the bonds and the energy is absorbed by the material as heat.
[src:dielectric-materials/permittivity] This is why microwave ovens work very well for materials containing water.
[src:dielectric-materials/permittivity] There are two maxima of the imaginary component (the absorptive index) of water, one at the microwave frequency, and the other at far ultraviolet (UV) frequency.
[src:dielectric-materials/permittivity] Both of these resonances are at higher frequencies than the operating frequency of microwave ovens.
[src:dielectric-materials/permittivity] At moderate frequencies, the energy is too high to cause rotation, yet too low to affect electrons directly, and is absorbed in the form of resonant molecular vibrations.
[src:dielectric-materials/permittivity] In water, this is where the absorptive index starts to drop sharply, and the minimum of the imaginary permittivity is at the frequency of blue light (optical regime).
[src:dielectric-materials/permittivity] At high frequencies (such as UV and above), molecules cannot relax, and the energy is purely absorbed by atoms, exciting electron energy levels.
[src:dielectric-materials/permittivity] Thus, these frequencies are classified as ionizing radiation.
[src:dielectric-materials/permittivity] While carrying out a complete *ab initio* (that is, first-principles) modelling is now computationally possible, it has not been widely applied yet.
[src:dielectric-materials/permittivity] Thus, a phenomenological model is accepted as being an adequate method of capturing experimental behaviors.
[src:dielectric-materials/permittivity] The Debye model and the Lorentz model use a first-order and second-order (respectively) lumped system parameter linear representation (such as an RC and an LRC resonant circuit).
[src:dielectric-materials/permittivity] The relative permittivity of a material can be found by a variety of static electrical measurements.
[src:dielectric-materials/permittivity] The complex permittivity is evaluated over a wide range of frequencies by using different variants of dielectric spectroscopy, covering nearly 21 orders of magnitude from 10−6 to 1015 hertz.
[src:dielectric-materials/permittivity] Also, by using cryostats and ovens, the dielectric properties of a medium can be characterized over an array of temperatures.
[src:dielectric-materials/permittivity] In order to study systems for such diverse excitation fields, a number of measurement setups are used, each adequate for a special frequency range.
[src:dielectric-materials/permittivity] Various microwave measurement techniques are outlined in Chen *et al.* Typical errors for the Hakki–Coleman method employing a puck of material between conducting planes are about 0.3%.
[src:dielectric-materials/permittivity] At infrared and optical frequencies, a common technique is ellipsometry.
[src:dielectric-materials/permittivity] Dual polarisation interferometry is also used to measure the complex refractive index for very thin films at optical frequencies.
[src:dielectric-materials/permittivity] For the 3D measurement of dielectric tensors at optical frequency, Dielectric tensor tomography can be used.
[src:dielectric-materials/polarization-density] In classical electromagnetism, **polarization density** (or **electric polarization**, or simply **polarization**) is the vector field that expresses the volumetric density of permanent or induced electric dipole moments in a dielectric material.
[src:dielectric-materials/polarization-density] When a dielectric is placed in an external electric field, its atoms or molecules gain electric dipole moment and the dielectric is said to be polarized.
[src:dielectric-materials/polarization-density] Electric polarization of a given dielectric material sample is defined as the quotient of electric dipole moment (a vector quantity, expressed as coulombs-meters (C⋅m) in SI units) to volume (in meters cubed).
[src:dielectric-materials/polarization-density] Polarization density is denoted mathematically by **P**; in SI units, it is expressed in coulombs per square meter (C/m2).
[src:dielectric-materials/polarization-density] Polarization density also describes how a material responds to an applied electric field as well as the way the material changes the electric field, and can be used to calculate the forces that result from those interactions.
[src:dielectric-materials/polarization-density] It can be compared to magnetization, which is the measure of the corresponding response of a material to a magnetic field in magnetism.
[src:dielectric-materials/polarization-density] Similar to ferromagnets, which have a non-zero permanent magnetization even if no external magnetic field is applied, ferroelectric materials have a non-zero polarization in the absence of external electric field.
[src:dielectric-materials/polarization-density] An external electric field that is applied to a dielectric material, causes a displacement of bound charged elements.
[src:dielectric-materials/polarization-density] A ***bound charge*** is a charge that is associated with an atom or molecule within a material.
[src:dielectric-materials/polarization-density] It is called "bound" because it is not free to move within the material like ***free charges***.
[src:dielectric-materials/polarization-density] Positive charged elements are displaced in the direction of the field, and negative charged elements are displaced opposite to the direction of the field.
[src:dielectric-materials/polarization-density] The molecules may remain neutral in charge, yet an electric dipole moment forms.
[src:dielectric-materials/polarization-density] In general, the dipole moment $\Delta \mathbf {p}$ changes from point to point within the dielectric.
[src:dielectric-materials/polarization-density] The net charge appearing as a result of polarization is called bound charge and denoted $Q_{\text{b}}$ .
[src:dielectric-materials/polarization-density] This definition of polarization density as a "dipole moment per unit volume" is widely adopted, though in some cases it can lead to ambiguities and paradoxes.
[src:dielectric-materials/polarization-density] Let a volume d*V* be isolated inside the dielectric.
[src:dielectric-materials/polarization-density] Due to polarization the positive bound charge $\mathrm {d} q_{\text{b}}^{+}$ will be displaced a distance **d** relative to the negative bound charge $\mathrm {d} q_{\text{b}}^{-}$ , giving rise to a dipole moment $\mathrm {d} \mathbf {p} =\mathrm {d} q_{\text{b}}\mathbf {d}$ .
[src:dielectric-materials/polarization-density] where $\rho _{\text{b}}$ is the density of the bound charge in the volume under consideration.
[src:dielectric-materials/polarization-density] It is clear from the definition above that the dipoles are overall neutral and thus $\rho _{\text{b}}$ is balanced by an equal density of opposite charges within the volume.
[src:dielectric-materials/polarization-density] Charges that are not balanced are part of the free charge discussed below.
[src:dielectric-materials/polarization-density] Let a surface area S envelope part of a dielectric.
[src:dielectric-materials/polarization-density] Upon polarization negative and positive bound charges will be displaced.
[src:dielectric-materials/polarization-density] Let *d*1 and *d*2 be the distances of the bound charges $\mathrm {d} q_{\text{b}}^{-}$ and $\mathrm {d} q_{\text{b}}^{+}$ , respectively, from the plane formed by the element of area d*A* after the polarization.
[src:dielectric-materials/polarization-density] And let d*V*1 and d*V*2 be the volumes enclosed below and above the area d*A*.
[src:dielectric-materials/polarization-density] By the divergence theorem, Gauss's law for the field **P** can be stated in *differential form* as: $-\rho _{\text{b}}=\nabla \cdot \mathbf {P} ,$ where ∇ · **P** is the divergence of the field **P** through a given surface containing the bound charge density $\rho _{\text{b}}$ .
[src:dielectric-materials/polarization-density] By the divergence theorem we have that $-Q_{\text{b}}=\iiint _{V}\nabla \cdot \mathbf {P} \ \mathrm {d} V,$ for the volume V containing the bound charge $Q_{\text{b}}$ .
[src:dielectric-materials/polarization-density] where *ε*0 is the electric constant, and χ is the electric susceptibility of the medium.
[src:dielectric-materials/polarization-density] Note that in this case χ simplifies to a scalar, although more generally it is a tensor.
[src:dielectric-materials/polarization-density] This is a particular case due to the *isotropy* of the dielectric.
[src:dielectric-materials/polarization-density] The expression in the integral is Gauss's law for the field **E** which yields the total charge, both free $(Q_{\text{f}})$ and bound $(Q_{\text{b}})$ , in the volume V enclosed by S.
[src:dielectric-materials/polarization-density] Since within a homogeneous dielectric there can be no free charges $(\rho _{\text{f}}=0)$ , by the last equation it follows that there is no bulk bound charge in the material $(\rho _{\text{b}}=0)$ .
[src:dielectric-materials/polarization-density] And since free charges can get as close to the dielectric as to its topmost surface, it follows that polarization only gives rise to surface bound charge density (denoted $\sigma _{\text{b}}$ to avoid ambiguity with the volume bound charge density $\rho _{\text{b}}$ ).
[src:dielectric-materials/polarization-density] $\sigma _{\text{b}}$ may be related to **P** by the following equation: $\sigma _{\text{b}}=\mathbf {\hat {n}} _{\text{out}}\cdot \mathbf {P}$ where $\mathbf {\hat {n}} _{\text{out}}$ is the normal vector to the surface *S* pointing outwards.
[src:dielectric-materials/polarization-density] The class of dielectrics where the polarization density and the electric field are not in the same direction are known as *anisotropic* materials.
[src:dielectric-materials/polarization-density] This relation shows, for example, that a material can polarize in the x direction by applying a field in the z direction, and so on.
[src:dielectric-materials/polarization-density] The case of an anisotropic dielectric medium is described by the field of crystal optics.
[src:dielectric-materials/polarization-density] As in most electromagnetism, this relation deals with macroscopic averages of the fields and dipole density, so that one has a continuum approximation of the dielectric materials that neglects atomic-scale behaviors.
[src:dielectric-materials/polarization-density] The polarizability of individual particles in the medium can be related to the average susceptibility and polarization density by the Clausius–Mossotti relation.
[src:dielectric-materials/polarization-density] In general, the susceptibility is a function of the frequency ω of the applied field.
[src:dielectric-materials/polarization-density] When the field is an arbitrary function of time t, the polarization is a convolution of the Fourier transform of *χ*(*ω*) with the **E**(*t*).
[src:dielectric-materials/polarization-density] This reflects the fact that the dipoles in the material cannot respond instantaneously to the applied field, and causality considerations lead to the Kramers–Kronig relations.
[src:dielectric-materials/polarization-density] If the polarization **P** is not linearly proportional to the electric field **E**, the medium is termed *nonlinear* and is described by the field of nonlinear optics.
[src:dielectric-materials/polarization-density] In ferroelectric materials, there is no one-to-one correspondence between **P** and **E** at all because of hysteresis.
[src:dielectric-materials/polarization-density] The behavior of electric fields (**E**, **D**), magnetic fields (**B**, **H**), charge density (ρ) and current density (**J**) are described by Maxwell's equations in matter.
[src:dielectric-materials/polarization-density] where $\rho$ is the total charge density.
[src:dielectric-materials/polarization-density] This is known as the constitutive equation for electric fields.
[src:dielectric-materials/polarization-density] Here *ε*0 is the electric permittivity of empty space.
[src:dielectric-materials/polarization-density] In this equation, **P** is the (negative of the) field induced in the material when the "fixed" charges, the dipoles, shift in response to the total underlying field **E**, whereas **D** is the field due to the remaining charges, known as "free" charges.
[src:dielectric-materials/polarization-density] In general, **P** varies as a function of **E** depending on the medium, as described later in the article.
[src:dielectric-materials/polarization-density] In many problems, it is more convenient to work with **D** and the free charges than with **E** and the total charge.
[src:dielectric-materials/polarization-density] Therefore, a polarized medium, by way of Green's theorem can be split into four components.
[src:dielectric-materials/polarization-density] where **J**f is the free-charge current density, and the second term is the magnetization current density (also called the *bound current density*), a contribution from atomic-scale magnetic dipoles (when they are present).
[src:dielectric-materials/polarization-density] In a simple approach the polarization inside a solid is not, in general, uniquely defined.
[src:dielectric-materials/polarization-density] Because a bulk solid is periodic, one must choose a unit cell in which to compute the polarization (see figure).
[src:dielectric-materials/polarization-density] In other words, two people, Alice and Bob, looking at the same solid, may calculate different values of **P**, and neither of them will be wrong.
[src:dielectric-materials/polarization-density] For example, if Alice chooses a unit cell with positive ions at the top and Bob chooses the unit cell with negative ions at the top, their computed **P** vectors will have opposite directions.
[src:dielectric-materials/polarization-density] Alice and Bob will agree on the microscopic electric field **E** in the solid, but disagree on the value of the displacement field $\mathbf {D} =\varepsilon _{0}\mathbf {E} +\mathbf {P}$ .
[src:dielectric-materials/polarization-density] Even though the value of **P** is not uniquely defined in a bulk solid, *variations* in **P** *are* uniquely defined.
[src:dielectric-materials/polarization-density] If the crystal is gradually changed from one structure to another, there will be a current inside each unit cell, due to the motion of nuclei and electrons.
[src:dielectric-materials/polarization-density] This current results in a macroscopic transfer of charge from one side of the crystal to the other, and therefore it can be measured with an ammeter (like any other current) when wires are attached to the opposite sides of the crystal.
[src:dielectric-materials/polarization-density] The time-integral of the current is proportional to the change in **P**.
[src:dielectric-materials/polarization-density] The current can be calculated in computer simulations (such as density functional theory); the formula for the integrated current turns out to be a type of Berry's phase.
[src:dielectric-materials/polarization-density] The non-uniqueness of **P** is not problematic, because every measurable consequence of **P** is in fact a consequence of a continuous change in **P**.
[src:dielectric-materials/polarization-density] For example, when a material is put in an electric field **E**, which ramps up from zero to a finite value, the material's electronic and ionic positions slightly shift.
[src:dielectric-materials/polarization-density] This changes **P**, and the result is electric susceptibility (and hence permittivity).
[src:dielectric-materials/polarization-density] As another example, when some crystals are heated, their electronic and ionic positions slightly shift, changing **P**.
[src:dielectric-materials/polarization-density] In all cases, the properties of interest are associated with a *change* in **P**.
[src:dielectric-materials/polarization-density] In what is now called the *modern theory of polarization*, the polarization is defined as a difference.
[src:dielectric-materials/polarization-density] Any structure which has inversion symmetry has zero polarization; there is an identical distribution of positive and negative charges about an inversion center.
[src:dielectric-materials/polarization-density] If the material deforms there can be a polarization due to the charge in the charge distribution.
[src:dielectric-materials/polarization-density] Another problem in the definition of **P** is related to the arbitrary choice of the "unit volume", or more precisely to the system's *scale*.
[src:dielectric-materials/polarization-density] For example, at *microscopic* scale a plasma can be regarded as a gas of *free* charges, thus **P** should be zero.
[src:dielectric-materials/polarization-density] On the contrary, at a *macroscopic* scale the same plasma can be described as a continuous medium, exhibiting a permittivity $\varepsilon (\omega )\neq 1$ and thus a net polarization **P** ≠ **0**.
